\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
101.1. At the start of a game, each player shuffles his or her own deck so that the cards are in a random order. Each player may then shuffle his or her }{\i opponent\rquote s}{ deck.
\par 
\par 101.2. After the decks have been shuffled, the players determine who chooses which player goes first using any mutually agreeable method (flipping a coin, rolling dice, etc.). In a }{\i match}{
 of several games, the loser of the previous game decides who will take the first turn. If the previous game was a }{\i draw,}{ the person who determined who would take the first turn in the previous game decides.
\par 
\par 101.3. Once the starting player has been determined, each player sets his or her life total to 20 and }{\i draws}{ a }{\i hand}{ of seven cards.
\par 
\par 101.4. The player who plays first }{\i skips}{ the }{\i draw}{ }{\i step}{ (see rule 304, \'93Draw Step\'94) of his or her first turn.
\par 
\par 101.5. A player who is dissatisfied with his or her initial hand may }{\i mulligan.}{
 That player shuffles his or her hand back into the deck, then draws a new hand of six cards. He or she may repeat this process as many times as desired, drawing one fewer card each time, until the hand size reaches zero car
ds. Once the first player has decided to keep a hand, the second player may mulligan. Once both players are satisfied with their hands, the first player takes his or her turn.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 102. Winning and Losing
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {102.1. If a player\rquote s life total is 0 or less, he or sh
e loses the game the next time a player would receive }{\i priority.}{ (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)
\par 
\par 102.2. When a player is required to draw more cards than are left in his or her }{\i library,}{ he or she draws the remaining cards, then loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)
\par 
\par 102.3. A game immediately ends when either these rules or a card }{\i effect}{ states that a player loses or wins.
\par 
\par 102.4. If both players lose simultaneously, the game is a }{\i draw.}{
\par 
\par 102.5. If a player would both win and lose simultaneously, he or she loses.
\par 
\par 102.6. If the game somehow enters a \'93loop,\'94 repeating a sequence of }{\i events}{ with no way to stop, the game is a draw. Loops that contain an optional action don\rquote t result in a draw.
\par 
\par 102.7. A player may concede a game at any time.
\par 
\par 102.8 If a player has ten or more poison counters, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 103. The Golden Rule
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {103.1. The }{\b Magic}{ Golden Rule: Whenever a card\rquote 
s text directly contradicts these rules, the card takes precedence. The card overrides only the rule that applies to that specific situation. If an instruction requires taking an impossible action, it\rquote s ignored. 
(In many cases the card will specify consequences for this; if it doesn\rquote t, there\rquote s no effect.)
\par 
\par 103.2. When one effect says something }{\i can}{ happen and another says it }{\i can\rquote t}{, the \'93can\rquote t\'94 effect wins. For example, if one effect reads \'93You may play an additional land this turn\'94 and another reads \'93You can\rquote 
t play land cards this turn,\'94 the effect that keeps you from playing lands wins out. Note that adding abilities to cards and removing abilities from cards don\rquote t fall under this rule. See rule 407, \'93Adding and Removing Abilities.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par }{\f28 \page }{\f28\fs22 2. Cards
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {200. General
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {200.1. When a rule or text on a card refers to a \'93card,\'94 it means a }{\b 
Magic}{ card with a }{\b Magic}{ card front and the }{\b Magic}{ card back. Tokens aren\rquote t considered cards\emdash even an }{\i Unglue}{\i\expnd4\expndtw20 d}{\i\super \'99}{ card that represents a token isn\rquote 
t considered a card for rules purposes.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 201. Parts of a Card
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {201.1. The parts of a card are name, }{\i mana cost,}{ illustration, }{\i type,}
{ }{\i expansion symbol, text box,}{ }{\i power }{and}{\i  toughness}{, credit, legal text, and collector number. Some cards may have more than one of any or all of these parts.}{\i 
\par }{
\par 201.2. A card, spell, or permanent\rquote s }{\i characteristics}{ are name, mana cost, color, type and subtype, expansion symbol, rules text, power, and toughness. Any other information about a card, spell, or permanent isn\rquote 
t a characteristic. Characteristics don\rquote t include any other information, such as whether a permanent is tapped, a spell\rquote s target, a spell or permanent\rquote s controller, what a local enchantment enchants, and so on.}{\cf13 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 202. Name
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {202.1. The name of a card is printed on its upper left corner.
\par 
\par 202.2. Card text that refers to the card it\rquote s on by name means just that particular card and not any other duplicates of it, regardless of any name changes caused by game effects. Also, if a card has an effect on or grants an }{\i ability}{
 that includes that card\rquote s name to another card, the name refers only to the card generating the effect or granting the ability, not to duplicates of cards with the same name.}{\cf13 
\par }{
\par 202.3. Two cards have the same name if the English versions of their names are identical, regardless of anything else printed on the cards.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 203. Mana Cost
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {203.1. The mana cost of a card is indicated by }{\i mana symbols }{
printed on its upper right corner. Tokens and }{\i lands}{ have a mana cost of 0. }{\i Paying}{ a card\rquote s mana cost requires matching the }{\i color}{ of any colored mana symbols as well as paying the }{\i generic mana cost}{ indicated.
\par 
\par 203.2. A card is the color or colors of the mana symbols in its mana cost, regardless of the color of its border. For example, a card wi
th a mana cost of 2W is white, and one with a mana cost of 2WB is both white and black. Cards with no colored mana symbols in their mana costs are }{\i colorless}{. Cards with more than one of the five colored mana symbols in their mana costs are }{\i 
multicolored}{. Multicolored cards are printed with a gold frame, but this is not a requirement for a card to be multicolored.
\par 
\par 203.3. The }{\i converted mana cost}{ of a card is the total amount of mana in the mana cost, regardless of color (For example, a mana cost of 3UU translates to a converted mana cost of 5). The converted mana cost is a generic mana cost\emdash 
it may be paid with any combination of colored and/or colorless }{\i mana,}{ regardless of the colors in the }{\i spell\rquote s}{ mana cost.}{\cf13 
\par }{
\par 203.4. Any }{\i additional cost}{ listed in a card\rquote s rules text isn\rquote t part of the mana cost. (See rule 409, \'93Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\'94) Such }{\i costs}{ are paid at the same time as the spell\rquote s other costs.

\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 204. Illustration
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {204.1. The illustration is printed on the upper half of a card and has no gam
e significance. For example, a creature doesn\rquote t have the flying ability unless stated in its rules text, even if it\rquote s depicted as flying.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 205. Type
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
205.1. The type (and subtype, if applicable) of a card is printed directly below the illustration. (See rules 212\endash 215.)
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 206. Expansion Symbol
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {206.1. The expansion symbol indicates which }{\b Magic}{ set a card is from. It
\rquote s printed below the right edge of the illustration.
\par 
\par 206.2. The color of the expansion symbol indicates the rarity of the card within its set. A gold symbol signifies the card is rare; silver, uncommon; and black, common or basic land. (Prior to the }{\i Exodus}{\i\super \'99}{
 set, all expansion symbols were black, regardless of rarity. Also, prior to the }{\i Classic}{\i\super \'99}{\i  }{(Sixth Edition) set, }{\b Magic}{ basic sets didn\rquote t have expansion symbols at all.)
\par 
\par 206.3. A spell or ability that affects cards from a particular set \'93looks\'94 only for that set\rquote s expansion symbol. A card reprinted in the basic set receives the basic set\rquote s expansion symbol; any reprinted version of the card no longe
r counts as part of its original set unless it was reprinted with that set\rquote s expansion symbol. The first five editions of the basic set had no expansion symbol.}{\cf13 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 207. Text Box
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {207.1. The text box is printed on the lower half of the card. It usually contai
ns rules text stating what the card does and any special requirements for playing it.
\par 
\par 207.2. The text box may also contain italicized }{\i reminder text}{ (in parentheses), which summarizes a rule that applies to that card, and italicized }{\i flavor text, }{which has 
no game function, but like the illustration, adds artistic appeal to the game.}{\cf13 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 208. Power/Toughness
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {208.1. A creature card has two }{\i numbers}{
 separated by a slash printed on its lower right corner. The first number is the creature\rquote s power (the amount of }{\i damage}{ it deals in }{\i comba}{\i\expnd4\expndtw20 t}{); the second is its toughness (the amount of damage needed to }{\i 
destroy}{ it). For example, 2/3 means the creature has power 2 and toughness 3. Power and toughness can be modified or set to particular values by effects.
\par 
\par 208.2. Some creature cards have power and/or toughness of }{\b *}{, where }{\b *}{ is a value determined by the text in the creature\rquote s text box. As long as the creature card is }{\i in play,}{ the value of }{\b *}{
 is treated just as if that number were actually printed on the card. The }{\b *}{ is 0 while the card is not in play.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 209. Credit
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
209.1. The illustration credit for a card is printed directly below the text box. The credit has no effect on game play.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 210. Legal Text
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {210.1. Legal text (the fine print at the bottom of the card) lists the copyri
ght information. It has no effect on game play.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 211. Collector Number
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
211.1. Some card sets feature collector numbers. This information is printed in the form [card number]/[total cards in the set], immediately following the legal text. These numbers have no effect on game play.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 212. Card Type
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {212.1. All cards have one or more card types: }{\i artifact,}{ creature, }{\i 
enchantment,}{ }{\i instant,}{ land, or }{\i sorcery.}{ Only one multiple type\emdash }{\i artifact creature}{\emdash currently exists. The artifact creature type satisfies the criteri
a for any effect that applies to an artifact card or a creature card. A card\rquote s type appears below its illustration.
\par 
\par 212.2. Some card types include subtypes, printed on the same line. Creature subtypes (including those of artifact creatures) appear after a dash that follows their card type(s). Enchantment subtypes consist of the word \'93enchant\'94
 and the word(s) that follows it, such as \'93enchant creature\'94 or \'93enchant artifact.\'94 Land subtypes are not printed on the card type line (see rule 212.2c).
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 212.2a Creature subtypes are always a single word and are listed after \'93Creature,
\'94 separated by a long dash: \'93Creature \emdash  Minotaur,\'94 \'93Artifact Creature \emdash  Golem Legend,\'94 etc. Creature subtypes are one word each and are also called \'93creature types.\'94 Creature cards may have multiple creature types.

\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  \'93Creature \emdash  Minotaur\'94
 means the card is a creature with the Minotaur subtype. \'93Creature \emdash  Goblin Wizard\'94 means the card is a creature with the creature types Goblin and Wizard.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 212.2b Enchantment subtypes consist of the word \'93enchant\'94 and the word(s) that follows it: \'93enchant creature,\'94 \'93enchant land,\'94 etc. (}{\i\f28 \'93enchant world\'94}{\f28  isn\rquote 
t a type or subtype, but a special category of enchantment found only in some older sets). A card with the type \'93enchantment\'94 has no enchantment subtype. An enchantment subtype specifies what the enchantment can be legally attached to. }{\i\f28 \'93
Local enchantment\'94 }{\f28 and }{\i\f28 \'93global enchantment\'94}{\f28  aren\rquote t types or subtypes; they\rquote re categories of enchantments. (Also see rule 214.8, \'93Enchantments.\'94)
\par 
\par 212.2c Land subtypes are also called }{\i\f28 \'93land types\'94}{\f28  and are always the same as the name of the land card; they aren\rquote t listed on the type line. A card named \'93Island\'94 has land type \'93island\'94; a card named \'93
Karplusan Forest\'94 has land type \'93Karplusan Forest\'94 (remember that it isn\rquote t a forest or a basic land). Only lands with a basic land type get abilities just for being a given land type. (See rule 214.9e.) \'93Basic land\'94 and \'93
nonbasic land\'94 aren\rquote t types or subtypes; they\rquote re categories of lands.
\par 
\par 212.2d There are no subtypes for artifact cards, instant cards, or sorcery cards.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 213. Spell Type
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {213.1. Every nonland card is a spell while it\rquote 
s being played (see rules 409.1a\endash 409.1f) and while it\rquote s on the }{\i stack.}{ Once it\rquote s played, a card remains a spell until it }{\i resolves}{ or is }{\i countered.}{ For more information, see rule 401, \'93Spells.\'94
\par 
\par 213.2. A spell\rquote s spell type is the same as its card type. Its subtypes are the same as its card\rquote s subtypes.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 214. Permanent Type
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {214.1. A }{\i permanent}{
 is a card or token in play. Permanents stay in play unless moved to another }{\i zone}{ by an effect or rule. There are four types of permanents: artifacts, creatures, enchantments, and lands. Instant and sorcery cards can\rquote t come into play.
\par 
\par 214.2. A nontoken permanent\rquote s type(s) and subtype(s) are the same as those printed on its card. A token\rquote s type(s) and subtype(s) are set by the spell or ability that created it.}{\cf13 
\par }{
\par 214.3. A card becomes a permanent when it }{\i comes into play}{ and stops being a permanent when it }{\i leaves play}{. The term \'93card\'94 is often used to refer to a card that\rquote s not in play, such as a creature card in a player\rquote s hand. 
\'93Spell\'94 is often used to refer to a card while it\rquote s on the stack. \'93Spell card\'94 is used to refer to cards that aren\rquote t in play and aren\rquote t land cards. For more information, see rule 217, \'93Zones.\'94
\par 
\par 214.4. When a permanent\rquote s type or subtype changes, the new type(s) replaces any existing type(s). This changes only the permanent type\emdash the card type doesn\rquote 
t change. Counters, effects, and damage affecting the permanent remain with it, even if they are meaningless to the new type.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 214.4a Some effects change a permanent\rquote s type or subtype but specify that the permanent retains a prior type or subtype. In such cases, the retained type isn\rquote t replaced, but any other types the permanent has are replaced.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  An ability reads, \'93All lands are 1/1 creatures that are still lands.
\'94 The affected lands now have two types: creature and land. If there were any lands that also had the artifact type before the ability\rquote s effect applied to them, those lands would become \'93land creatures,\'94 not \'93artifact land creatures.
\'94 The effect allows them to retain the land type, but wipes out the artifact type.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 214.4b If a permanent\rquote 
s type changes, the subtypes of its old permanent type don\rquote t exist in any way under the new type. The subtype disappears completely for the entire time the card\rquote 
s permanent type is changed. This does not override the rule that a permanent retains its legendary status when its type changes (see rule 215.2).
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 214.5. The }{\i initial value}{ of a permanent\rquote s characte
ristic is the value printed on the card or specified by the spell or ability that created the token or changed the type of the permanent. A permanent-type-changing ability that changes one or more characteristics changes the initial values of those charac
teristics stated in the ability\rquote s text, not the current values. }{\i Continuous effects}{ that don\rquote t change a permanent\rquote s type affect current values of characteristics and can override characteristics set by type-changing abilities.

\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  A player plays an artifact\rquote s ability that reads \'93
2: This permanent is a 3/2 artifact creature.\'94 Later in the turn, the artifact creature is affected by an ability that reads \'93Target creature is 0/2.\'94 At this point, playing the ability of the artifact again won\rquote t do anything; be
cause the type-changing ability changes characteristics at the initial level, it can\rquote t override the effect. The artifact creature remains 0/2.}{\i0\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 214.6. Artifacts
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
214.6a Artifacts have no characteristics specific to their type. Because artifact spells have no colored mana in their mana costs, they\rquote 
re colorless, and the permanents they create are also colorless. Effects can give artifact spells or artifacts one or more colors, however.
\par 
\par 214.6b Artifact creatures combine the characteristics of both the creature and artifact types and are subject to spells and abilities that affect either or both types.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 214.7. Creatures
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
214.7a If a card instruction requires choosing a creature subtype, you must choose one, and only one, existing creature type.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  "Merfol
k" or "Wizard" is acceptable, but "Merfolk Wizard" is not. Words like \'93artifact,\'94 \'93opponent,\'94 \'93swamp,\'94 or \'93truck\'94 can\rquote t be chosen because they aren't creature types.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\f28 
\par }{\f28 214.7b Use the Oracle\'99 card reference when determining creature types. It can be found at }{\cs23\f6\ul\cf2 www.wizards.com/dci/main.asp?x=oracle}{\f28 .
\par }{
\par }{\f28 214.7c A creature\rquote s activated ability with the tap symbol in its activation cost can\rquote t be played unless the creature has been under its controller\rquote s control since the start of his or her most recent turn. A creature can\rquote 
t attack unless it has been under its controller\rquote s control since the start of his or her most recent turn. Ignore this rule for creatures with haste (see rule 502.5).}{
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {214.8. Enchantments
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 214.8a A }{\i\f28 global enchantment}{\f28  simply has \'93enchantment\'94
 as its type. }{\i\f28 Local enchantments}{\f28  comprise various subtypes: enchant artifact, enchant creature, enchant enchantment, enchant land, and enchant permanent.
\par 
\par 214.8b A global enchantment is put into play on the side of the player who controlled the spell that created it, like any other spell that creates a permanent.
\par 
\par 214.8c A local-enchantment spell requires a }{\i\f28 target}{\f28  whose type is indicated by the enchantment subtype. The local-enchantment permanent the
 spell puts into play must enchant that type of permanent and comes into play attached to the permanent the spell targeted. Any additional targeting requirements are indicated by phrases like \'93
[This card] can enchant only a [permanent with specified characteristics].\'94
 These restrictions apply to playing the spell, and they become restrictions on what the resulting permanent can enchant. Similar restrictions can limit what a permanent can be enchanted by. For example, a permanent might have an ability that reads \'93
[This card] can\rquote t be enchanted by [local enchantments with specified characteristics].\'94
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 
An enchant creature spell requires a target creature; a creature enchantment in play must enchant a creature. (See rules 420.5d and 214.8g.)
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 214.8d As part of playing a local-enchantment spell, the player announces the spell\rquote 
s target. The local enchantment comes into play attached to that target permanent. If a local enchantment is coming into play by any other means, the player putting it into play choos
es a permanent for it to enchant as it comes into play. In this case, the enchantment doesn\rquote 
t target the permanent, but the player still must choose a permanent that the enchantment can enchant. If no legal permanent is available, the enchantment remains in the zone from which it attempted to }{\i\f28 move}{\f28 
 instead of coming into play. The same rule applies to moving a local enchantment from one permanent to another. The permanent to which the enchantment is to be moved must be able to be enchanted by it. If it isn\rquote t legal, the enchantment doesn
\rquote t move.
\par 
\par 214.8e If a local enchantment is enchanting an illegal permanent or the permanent it was attached to no longer exists, the enchantment card is put into its }{\i\f28 owner\rquote s}{\f28  }{\i\f28 graveyard.}{\f28 
 (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)
\par 
\par 214.8f A local enchantment can\rquote t be attached to itself. If this occurs somehow, the local enchantment is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard as a }{\i\f28 state-based effect}{\f28  (see rule 420.5d).
\par 
\par 214.8g The permanent a local enchantment is attached to is called \'93enchanted.\'94 The enchantment \'93enchants\'94 or, in more casual terms, \'93is attached to\'94 that permanent.
\par 
\par 214.8h A local enchantment\rquote s abilities don\rquote t target the permanent it enchants unless they state they can target it. Only the enchantment spell targets the permanent it will enchant; the resulting enchantment permanent doesn\rquote 
t continue to target the enchanted permanent after the enchantment spell resolves. If a permanent \'93can\rquote t be enchanted\'94 in general or by enchantments with specified characteristics, it also can\rquote 
t be the target of a spell that would enchant it with such an enchantment.
\par 
\par 214.8i A local enchantment\rquote s }{\i\f28 controller}{\f28  is separate from the enchanted permanent\rquote s controller; the two need not be the same. Changing }{\i\f28 control}{\f28  of the permanent doesn\rquote t change contro
l of the enchantment, and vice versa. Only the enchantment\rquote s controller can play its abilities. However, if the enchantment adds an ability to the enchanted permanent (with \'93gains\'94 or \'93has\'94), that enchanted permanent\rquote 
s controller is the only one who can play that ability.
\par 
\par 214.8k An enchant world card is a global enchantment.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 214.9. Lands
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 214.9a A land card isn\rquote 
t a spell card, and at no time is it a spell. When a player plays a land card, it\rquote s simply put into play. The land card doesn\rquote t go on the stack, so players can\rquote t respond to it with instants or }{\i\f28 activated abilities.}{\f28 

\par 
\par 214.9b A player may normally play only one land card during each of his or her own turns, only during a }{\i\f28 main phase,}{\f28  and only when the stack is empty. Spells and abilities may allow the pl
aying of additional lands; playing an additional land in this way doesn\rquote t prevent a player from taking the normal action of playing a land. Players can\rquote 
t begin to play a land that an effect prohibits from being played. As a player plays a land, he or she a
nnounces whether he or she is using the once-per-turn action of playing a land. If not, he or she specifies which effect is allowing the additional land play. Spells and abilities may also allow you to \'93put\'94 lands into play. This isn\rquote 
t the same as \'93playing a land\'94 and doesn\rquote t count as the player\rquote s one land played during his or her turn.
\par 
\par 214.9c Each land card is in one of two categories: }{\i\f28 basic}{\f28  or }{\i\f28 nonbasic. }{\f28 Basic and nonbasic are not types or subtypes.}{\i\f28 
\par }{\f28 
\par 214.9d The basic land types are plains, island, swamp, 
mountain, and forest. A land with one of these words as its name is a basic land. Other lands can state that they are lands of one or more basic land types. A land that has one or more basic land types is not necessarily a basic land. Moreover, the name o
f a land with a single land type that\rquote s basic becomes that basic land-type word.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  Taiga is a land with the following text in its text box: \'93
Taiga is a mountain and a forest in addition to its type.\'94 Even though Taiga has two basic land types, it\rquote s not a basic land, because (a) its name doesn\rquote t match a basic land type word, and (b) it doesn\rquote t specify that it\rquote 
s basic.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 214.9e A land with a basic land type has an intrinsic ability to produce colored mana. (See rule 406.1, \'93Mana Abilities.\'94) The card is treated as if its text box read, \'93T: Add [mana symbol] to your mana pool,\'94 even if the text box doesn
\rquote t actually contain text. Plains produce white mana; islands, blue; swamps, black; mountains, red; and forests, green.
\par 
\par 214.9f If an effect changes a permanent into a basic land, the permanent no longer has its old land type and has only the }{\i\f28 mana ability}{\f28  of that basic land. It is now a basic land, and its name is that basic land\rquote 
s name. If that permanent was \'93Legendary,\'94 it is no longer. This rule doesn\rquote t apply to effects that cause a land to gain one or more land types in addition to its own.
\par 
\par 214.9g Any land that isn\rquote t a basic land is a nonbasic land. Basic and nonbasic are not types; they\rquote re categories.
\par 
\par 214.9h Unlike basic lands and lands that have one or more basic types, nonbasic lands don\rquote t necessarily have mana abilities.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 215. Legends and Legendary Types
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {215.1. The word }{\i Legend}{ or }{\i Legendary}{ may appear in a card\rquote 
s type or subtype. The permanent created when that card enters play is subject to the }{\i Legend rule}{ (see rule 420, \'93State-Based Effects\'94) as well as the rules for its type and subtype.
\par 
\par 215.2. \'93Legend\'94 is a creature type; \'93legendary\'94 is not. If a \'93legendary\'94 noncreature permanent }{\i becomes}{ a creature, it gets the creature type \'93Legend\'94 for as long as it\rquote s a creature. If a creature of type \'93Legend
\'94 becomes a noncreature permanent, it\rquote s a \'93legendary\'94 permanent of the new type. In other words, they mean the same thing, except that one refers to creatures and the other to noncreatures. 
\par 
\par 215.3. If an effect makes a non-Legend creature into a Legend, and the creature then becomes another permanent type, such as an enchantment, that effect may no longer apply (if the permanent is no longer a creature). If it doesn\rquote 
t, the resulting permanent will not be legendary.}{\cf13 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 216. Tokens
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
216.1. Some spells and abilities put a token creature into play. The token is controlled by whomever put it into play and owned by the controller of the spell or ability that created it. The rules text of the spell or ability may defin
e any number of characteristics for the token. These are the token permanent\rquote s initial values. A token doesn\rquote t have any characteristics not defined by the spell or ability that created it. }{\cgrid0 A token\rquote 
s creature type is the same as its name. A Goblin creature token, for example, is named Goblin and has the creature subtype Goblin. If a token\rquote 
s name is two words or more, it has the creature subtype for each of those words. For example, a Goblin Scout token is named Goblin Scout and has two creature subtypes: Goblin and Scout.}{ Once a token is in play, changing its name doesn\rquote 
t change its creature type, and vice versa.
\par 
\par 216.2. A token is subject to anything that affects permanents in general or that affects the token\rquote s type or subtype. A token isn\rquote t considered a card (even if represented by cards from other games or }{\i Unglued}{ cards) and isn\rquote 
t subject to any effect that specifically uses the word \'93card.\'94
\par 
\par 216.3. A token in a zone other than the in-play zone ceases to exist. This is a state-based effect. (Note that a token changing zones will set off }{\i triggered abilities}{ before the token ceases to exist.) Once a token has left play, it can\rquote 
t be returned to play by any means.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 217. Zones
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {217.1. A zone is a place where }{\b Magic }{
cards can be during a game. There are six basic zones: library,}{\i  }{hand, graveyard, in play, stack, and }{\i removed from the game}{. Each player has his or her own set of zones, except for the in-play and stack zones, which are shared.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 217.1a If a card would go to any library, graveyard, or hand other than its owner\rquote s, it goes to the corresponding zone of its owner\rquote s instead. If an instant or sorcery card would come into play, it remains in its previous zone instead.

\par 
\par 217.1b The order of cards in a library, in a graveyard, or on the stack can\rquote t be changed except when effects allow it. Cards in other zones can be arranged however their owners wish, although who controls those cards, whether they\rquote re }{
\i\f28 tapped,}{\f28  and what enchants them must remain clear to both players.
\par 
\par 217.1c A card that moves from one zone to another 
is treated as a new card. Effects connected with its previous location will no longer affect it. There are two exceptions to this rule: Effects that edit the characteristics of a spell on the stack will continue to apply to the permanent that spell create
s, and abilities that }{\i\f28 trigger}{\f28  when a card moves from one zone to another (for example, \'93When Rancor is put into a graveyard from play\'94) can find the card in the zone it moved to when the ability triggered.
\par 
\par 217.1d If a card or permanent would move from one zone to another, first determine what event is moving the card. Then apply any appropriate }{\i\f28 replacement effects}{\f28 
 to that event. If an effect tries to do two or more contradictory or mutually exclusive things to a particular card or permanent, that card or permanent\rquote s controller\emdash or its owner if it has no controller\emdash 
chooses what the effect does to the card or permanent. Then the event moves the card or permanent.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 217.2. Library
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 217.2a When a game begins, each player\rquote s deck becomes his or her library.

\par 
\par 217.2b Each library must be kept in a single face-down pile. Players can\rquote t look at or change the order of cards in a library.
\par 
\par 217.2c Any player may count the number of cards remaining in either player\rquote s library at any time.
\par 
\par 217.2d If an effect puts two or more cards on the top or bottom of a library at the same time, the owner of those cards may arrange them in any order. That library\rquote s owner doesn\rquote 
t reveal the order in which the cards go into his or her library.
\par 
\par 217.2e Some effects tell a player to play with the top card of his or her library revealed. If the top card of the player\rquote s library changes during the announcement of a spell or ability, the new top card won\rquote 
t be revealed until the announcement is complete.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\sl-200\slmult0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {217.3. Hand
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 217.3a The hand is where a playe
r holds cards that have been drawn but not yet played.
\par 
\par 217.3b Each player has a }{\i\f28 maximum hand size,}{\f28  which is normally seven cards. A player may have any number of cards in his or her hand, but as part of his or her }{\i\f28 cleanup}{\f28  }{\i\f28 step,}{\f28  the player must }{\i\f28 discard}{
\f28  excess cards down to the maximum hand size.
\par 
\par 217.3c A player may arrange his or her hand in any convenient fashion and look at it as much as he or she wishes. A player can\rquote t look at the cards in another player\rquote s hand but may count those cards at any time.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 217.4. Graveyard
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 217.4a A graveyard is a discard pile. Any card that\rquote 
s countered, discarded, destroyed, or }{\i\f28 sacrificed}{\f28  is put on top of its owner\rquote s graveyard, as is any instant or sorcery spell that\rquote s finished resolving. Each player\rquote s graveyard starts out empty.
\par 
\par 217.4b Each graveyard is kept in a single face-up pile. A player can examine the cards in any graveyard at any time but can\rquote t change their order.
\par 
\par 217.4c If an effect puts two or more cards into the same graveyard at the same time, the owner of those cards may arrange them in any order.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 217.5. In Play
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
217.5a Most of the area between the players represents the in-play zone. The in-play zone starts out empty. Permanents a player controls (other than local enchantments enchanting the other player\rquote s permanents) are kept in front of him or her.

\par 
\par 217.5b A spell or ability affects and checks only the in-play zone unless it specifically mentions a player or another zone. Permanents exist only in the in-play zone. Only permanents are legal targets for spells 
and abilities, unless a spell or ability (a) specifies that it can target a player or a card in another zone, or (b) affects an object that can\rquote t exist in the in-play zone, such as a spell.
\par 
\par 217.5c Whenever a card enters the in-play zone, it\rquote s considered a brand-new permanent and has no relationship to any previous permanent represented by the same card (see rule 217.8, \'93Phased-Out\'94).
\par 
\par 217.5d A card not in the in-play zone isn\rquote t \'93in play\'94 and isn\rquote t considered tapped or untapped. Cards that aren\rquote t either in play or on the stack aren\rquote t controlled by either player.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 217.6. Stack
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
217.6a When a spell or ability is played, it goes on top of the stack and waits to resolve. The stack keeps track of the order that spells and/or abilities were added to it. (See rule 408, \'93Timing of Spells and Abilities,\'94 and rule 409.1.)
\par 
\par 217.6b When a spell is played, it goes on the stack face up. Other spells or abilities played in response go on top of it. Abilities that go on the stack are represented by imaginary cards called }{\i\f28 pseudospells}{\f28 
. Each pseudospell from an activated or triggered ability has the text of the ability that created it. The controller of a pseudospell from an activated ability is the player who played the ability. The controller of a pseudospell from a triggered
 ability is the player who controlled the ability\rquote s }{\i\f28 source}{\f28  when it triggered.
\par 
\par 217.6c When both players }{\i\f28 pass}{\f28  in succession, the top (last-played) spell or ability resolves. If the stack is empty when both players pass, the current }{\i\f28 step}{\f28  or }{\i\f28 phase}{\f28  ends and the next begins.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 217.7. Removed from the Game
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
217.7a Effects can remove cards from the game. Some effects may provide a way for the card to return to play and use the term }{\i\f28 \'93set aside.\'94}{\f28  Cards that are set aside this way are still removed from the game, even
 though that removal may be temporary.}{\f28\cf13 
\par }{\f28 
\par 217.7b Cards in the removed-from-the-game zone are kept face up and may be examined by either player at any time. Cards \'93removed from the game face down\'94 can\rquote t be examined by either player except when instructions allow it.
\par 
\par 217.7c Cards that might return to play should be kept in separate piles to keep track of their respective ways of returning. Cards with no way of returning may be kept in one pile for each player, regardless of what removed them.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 217.8. Phased-Out
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 217.8a Permanents that phase out are placed in the }{\i\f28 phased-out}{\f28 
 zone. (See rule 502.15, \'93Phasing.\'94)
\par 
\par 217.8b Cards in the phased-out zone may be examined by either player at any time.
\par 
\par 217.8c Phased-out cards do not count as tapped or untapped, nor are they controlled by anyone. However, cards in this zone \'93remember\'94 their previous state and return to play in the same state as when they left. (See rule 502.15, \'93Phasing.\'94
) This is an exception to rule 217.5c.
\par  
\par 217.8d Tokens in the phased-out zone cease to exist. This is a state-based effect (see rule 420, \'93State-Based Effects\'94). Any local enchantments that were attached to those token creatures}{\f28\cf13  }{\f28 
remain phased out for the rest of the game.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 217.9 Ante
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 217.9a Earlier versions of the }{\b\f28 Magic}{\f28  rules included an }{\i\f28 ante}
{\f28  rule as a way of playing \'93for keeps.\'94 Playing }{\b\f28 Magic}{\f28  for ante is now considered an optional variation on the game, and it\rquote s allowed only where it\rquote 
s not forbidden by law or by other rules. Playing for ante is strictly forbidden under the DCI Universal Tournament Rules.
\par 
\par 217.9b When playing for ante, each player puts one random card from his or her deck into his or her ante zone at the beginning of the game. Cards in the ante zone may be examined by either player at any time. At the end of the game, the winn
er becomes the owner of the cards in each player\rquote s ante zone.
\par 
\par 217.9c A few cards have the text \'93Remove [this card] from your deck before playing if you\rquote re not playing for ante.\'94 This text isn\rquote t an ability. These are the only cards that can add or remove cards from a player\rquote 
s ante zone, or change a card\rquote s owner.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par \page 3. Turn Structure
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 300. General
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {300.1. A turn consists of five phases, in this order: }{\i beginning,}{
 first main, }{\i combat,}{ second}{\i  }{main, and }{\i end.}{ Each of these phases takes place every turn, even if nothing happens during the phase. The beginning, combat, and end phases are further broken down into steps, which proceed in order.
\par 
\par 300.2. A phase or step ends when the stack is empty and both players pass in succession. No game events can occur between turns, phases, or steps. (Simply having the stack become empty doesn\rquote 
t cause the phase or step to end; both players have to pass with the stack empty. Because of this, each player always gets a chance to add new things to the stack before the current phase or step ends.)
\par 
\par 300.3. When a phase or step ends, any effects scheduled to last \'93until end of\'94 that phase or step}{\cf13  }{expire. When a phase or step begins, any effects scheduled to last \'93until\'94 that phase or step expire. }{\cgrid0 Effects that last \'93
until end of combat\'94 expire at the end of the combat phase, not at the beginning of the end of combat step. }{Effects that last \'93until end of turn\'94 are subject to special rules; see rule 314.1b.
\par 
\par 300.4. When a phase ends (but not a step), any unused mana left in a player\rquote s }{\i mana pool}{ is lost. That player loses 1 life for each one mana lost this way. This is called }{\i mana}{ }{\i burn.}{
 Note that mana burn is loss of life, not damage, so it can\rquote t be prevented or altered by effects that affect damage. (See rule 406.1, \'93Mana Abilities.\'94)
\par 
\par 300.5. When a phase or step begins, any abilities that trigger \'93at the beginning of\'94 that phase or step are added to the stack.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK1}300.6. Some spells and abilities can give a player extra turns. They do this by adding the turns directly after the current turn. If a 
player gets multiple extra turns or if both players get extra turns during a single turn, the extra turns are added one at a time. The most recently created turn will be taken first.{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK1}
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 301. Beginning Phase
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {301.1. The beginning phase consists of three steps, in this order: }{\i 
untap, upkeep,}{ and }{\i draw.}{
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 302. Untap Step
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {302.1. First, the }{\i active player}{
 determines which permanents he or she controls will untap. (Normally they all do, but effects}{\cf13  }{may modify this.) Then he or she untaps them all simultaneously. Effects can keep one or more of a player\rquote s permanents from untapping normally.

\par 
\par 302.2. No player receives priority during the untap step, so no spells or abilities can be played or resolved. Any ability that triggers during this step will be held until a player would receive priority during the upkeep step. (See rule 303, \'93
Upkeep Step.\'94)
\par 
\par 302.3 Before a player untaps his or her permanents, all permanents with }{\i phasing}{ that player controls phase out, and all permanents that player controlled when they phased out simultaneously phase in. (See rule 217.8, \'93Phased-Out,\'94
 and rule 502.15, \'93Phasing.\'94)
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 303. Upkeep Step
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
303.1. As the upkeep step begins, any abilities that trigger at the beginning of that upkeep step or that triggered during that turn\rquote s untap step go on the stack. (See rule 404, \'93Triggered Abilities.\'94
) Once all such abilities have gone onto the stack, the active player gets priority. Then players may play spells and abilities.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 304. Draw Step
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {304.1. As the draw step begins, any abilities that trigger at t
he beginning of the draw step go on the stack. (See rule 404, \'93Triggered Abilities.\'94) Then the draw step action\emdash the active player drawing a card\emdash goes on the stack. This action is a triggered ability, but it isn\rquote 
t controlled by either player. It simply goes on the stack on top of all abilities players control that trigger at the beginning of the draw step. The draw step action can\rquote 
t be countered. Then the active player gets priority, and players may play spells and abilities.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 305. Main Phase
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {305.1. There a
re two main phases in a turn. In each turn, the first main phase, known as the }{\i precombat}{ main phase, and second main phase, known as the }{\i postcombat}{ main phase, are separated by the combat phase (see rule 306, \'93Combat Phase\'94
). The precombat and postcombat main phases are individually and collectively known as the \'93main phase.\'94
\par 
\par 305.2. The main phase has no steps, so a}{\cf13  }{main phase ends when both players pass in succession while the stack is empty.
\par 
\par 305.3. As the main phase begins, any abilities that trigger at the beginning of that main phase go on the stack. (See rule 404, \'93Triggered Abilities.\'94
) Then the active player gets priority, and players may play spells and abilities. (This is the only phase in which a player can normally play artifact, creature, enchantment, and sorcery spells, and only the active player may play these spells.)
\par 
\par 305.4. During either main phase, the active player may play one land from his or her hand if the stack is empty, if the player has priority, and if he or she hasn\rquote t yet taken this special action this turn. (See rule 214.9, \'93Lands.\'94
) This action doesn\rquote t use the stack and it isn\rquote t a spell or ability of any kind. It can\rquote t be countered, and players can\rquote t respond to it with instants or activated abilities.}{\cf13 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 306. Combat Phase
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {306.1. 
The combat phase has five steps, which proceed in order: beginning of combat, declare attackers, declare blockers, combat damage, and end of combat. The declare blockers and combat damage steps are skipped if no creatures are declared as attackers (see ru
le 308.4).
\par 
\par 306.2. A creature is }{\i removed from combat}{ if it stops being a creature (as a result of leaving play by any means, such as by being destroyed or removed from the game), if it }{\i regenerates}{ (see rule 419.6b), or if its controller changes. \'93
Removed from combat\'94 means the creature stops being an attacking, blocking, blocked, and/or }{\i unblocked creature.}{
 Once a creature has been declared as an attacking or blocking creature, spells or abilities that would have kept that creature from attacking or blocking don\rquote t remove the creature from combat. Tapping or untapping a creature that\rquote 
s already been declared as an attacker or blocker doesn\rquote t remove it from combat and doesn\rquote t prevent its }{\i combat damage.}{\cf13 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 307. Beginning of Combat Step
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {307.1. As this step begins, t
riggered abilities (if any) are added to the stack, and then the active player gets priority to play spells and abilities.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 308. Declare Attackers Step
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
308.1. The active player declares which, if any, creatures he or she controls will attack}{\i .}{ Only creatures can }{\i attack,}{ and the following creatures can\rquote t attack: tapped creatures (even those that can attack without tapping), }{\i Walls,
}{ and creatures the active player didn\rquote t control continuously since the beginning of the turn. This declaration is simultaneous, not sequential, and doesn\rquote 
t go on the stack. Any triggered ability generated during this action waits until a player would receive priority.
\par 
\par 308.2. The active player determines whether the attack is legal. (See section 5, \'93Additional Rules.\'94) If it is, he o
r she taps all creatures that will attack. Tapping a creature when it is declared as an attacker is not a cost; attacking simply causes creatures to become tapped. Then the player pays all required }{\i costs.}{
 (See rule 409.1f.) The active player may play mana abilities at this time only if an attack cost includes a mana payment.
\par 
\par 308.3. If the proposed attack isn\rquote t legal or the active player can\rquote t pay all required costs, all actions described in rules 308.1 and 308.2 are canceled. Then the active player redeclares which creatures will attack. (See rule 422, \'93
Handling Illegal Actions.\'94)
\par 
\par 308.4. If no creatures are declared as attackers, the game proceeds directly to the end of combat step, skipping the remainder of the declare attackers step as well as the entire declare blockers and combat damage steps.
\par 
\par 308.5. A creature becomes an }{\i attacking creature}{ when it has been declared as part of a legal attack and all attack costs have been paid, but only if it\rquote s controlled by the active player. It remains an attacking creature until it\rquote 
s removed from combat or the combat phase ends, whichever comes first. The nonactive player is considered to have been }{\i attacked}{ that turn at this time if one or more creatures are attacking.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 308.5a A creature is considered }{\i\f28 attacking alone}{\f28  if it\rquote s the sole creature declared as an attacker in a given combat phase.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 308.6. After a legal attack has been declared and all required costs have been paid, the active player receives priority to play spells and abilities.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 309. Declare Blockers Step
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
309.1. The defending player declares which, if any, creatures he or she controls are blocking and which attacking creature each one }{\i blocks.}{ Noncreature permanents and tapped creatures can\rquote 
t be declared as blockers. Each creature may block only one attacking creature, although any number of creatures may block the same attacking creature. (Note that blocking doesn\rquote 
t cause a creature to tap.) This declaration is simultaneous, not sequential, and doesn\rquote t go on the stack. Any triggered ability generated during this action waits until a player would receive priority.
\par }\pard \s17\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {309.2. The defending player determines whether the block is legal. (See section 5, \'93Additional Rules.\'94
) If it is, he or she pays all required costs. A player may play mana abilities at this time only if a blocking cost that player could pay includes a mana payment.
\par }\pard \s17\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {309.3. If the proposed block isn\rquote t legal or the defending player can\rquote 
t pay all required costs, all actions described in rules 309.1 and 309.2 are canceled. Then the defending player redeclares blocking creatures. (See rule 422, \'93Handling Illegal Actions.\'94)
\par }\pard \s17\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {309.4. A creature becomes a }{\i blocking creature}{
 when it has been declared as part of a legal block and all block costs have been paid, but only if it\rquote s controlled by the defending player. An attacking creature with one or more creatures declared as blockers for it becomes a }{\i blocked creatur
}{\i\expnd2\expndtw10 e}{; one with no blockers becomes an unblocked creature}{\i .}{ The creature\rquote s status remains unchanged until the creature is removed from combat or the combat phase ends, whichever comes first.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 309.4a A creature is considered }{\i\f28 blocking alone}{\f28  if it\rquote s the sole creature declared as a blocker in a given combat phase.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {309.5. After all legal blocks have been declared and all required costs have been paid, the active p
layer receives priority to play spells and abilities.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 310. Combat Damage Step
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
310.1. First the active player announces how each attacking creature will assign its combat damage. Then the defending player announces how each blocking creature will assign its combat damage. (See also rule 502.2, \'93First Strike.\'94
) A player may divide a creature\rquote s combat damage as he or she chooses among the legal recipients. Dividing combat damage is subject to the following restrictions:
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 310.1a Each attacking creature and each blocking creature will assign combat damage equal to its power.
\par 
\par 310.1b An unblocked creature will assign all its combat damage to the defending player.
\par 
\par 310.1c A blocked creature will assign combat damage, divided as its controller chooses, to the creatures blocking it. If no creatures are currently blocking it (if, for example, they were destroyed or removed from combat), it will assign no combat damage.

\par 
\par 310.1d A blocking creature will assign combat damage, divided as its controller chooses (no fractions), to the attacking creatures it\rquote s blocking. If it isn\rquote 
t currently blocking any creatures (if, for example, they were destroyed or removed from combat), it will assign no combat damage.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 310.2. All assignments of combat damage go on the stack as though they were a single pseudospell. Then the active player receives priority to play spells and abilities.
\par 
\par 310.3. Although combat-damage assignments go on the stack, they aren\rquote t spells or abilities, so they can\rquote t be countered.
\par 
\par 310.4. Combat damage resolves as though it were a pseudospell. When it resolves, it\rquote 
s dealt as originally assigned. This happens even if the creature dealing damage is no longer in play, its power has changed, or the creature receiving damage has left combat. (Note that the source of th
e damage is the creature as it currently exists, or as it most recently existed if it is no longer in play.) If a creature that was supposed to receive damage is no longer in play or is no longer a creature, the damage assigned to it isn\rquote 
t dealt. After combat damage finishes resolving, the active player gets priority.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 311. End of Combat Step
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {311.1. All \'93at end of combat\'94
 abilities trigger and go on the stack. (See rule 404, \'93Triggered Abilities.\'94) Then the active player receives priority to play spells and abilities.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 312. End Phase
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {312.1. The end phase consists of two steps: }{\i end of turn}{ and }{\i cleanup.
}{
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 313. End of Turn Step
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {313.1. As the end of turn step begins, all abilities that trigger \'93
at end of turn\'94 go on the stack. (See rule 404, \'93Triggered Abilities.\'94) The active player gets priority, then players may play spells and abilities.
\par 
\par 313.2. If \'93at end of turn\'94-triggered abilities are created or if cards with \'93at end of turn\'94-triggered abilities come into play after preexisting ones have already gone on the stack at the beginning of the end of turn step, those abilities won
\rquote t go on the stack until the next turn\rquote s end phase. In other words, the step doesn\rquote t \'93back up\'94 so new \'93at end of turn\'94-triggered abilities can go on the stack.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 314. Cleanup Step
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {314.1. The cleanup step proceeds in the following order.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 314.1a First, if the active player\rquote s hand contains more cards than his or her 
}{\i\f28 maximum hand size}{\f28  (normally seven), he or she discards enough cards to reduce the hand size to that number. This action doesn\rquote t go on the stack.
\par 
\par 314.1b Then, simultaneously, all damage is removed from permanents and all \'93until end of turn\'94 and \'93this turn\'94 effects end. This action doesn\rquote t go on the stack.
\par 
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-450\li1080\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1080\itap0 {\f28 314.1c Then, only if the conditions for any state-based effects exist or 
if any triggered abilities are waiting to be put onto the stack, the active player receives priority to play spells and abilities. Once the stack is empty and both players pass, another cleanup step begins. Otherwise, no player receives priority and the s
tep ends.
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 \page 4. Spells, Abilities, and Effects
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 400. General
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {400.1. An ability is text in a card\rquote 
s text box that generates an effect. Reminder text, flavor text, characteristic-setting text, and spell text are not abilities. Reminder text and flavor text al
ways appear in italics. Characteristic-setting text is any text that states that that card, permanent, or spell \'93is\'94 a particular characteristic. Spell text is any text that\rquote 
s followed as a spell is played or is resolving. Abilities generate effects only from the in-play zone unless they state otherwise. Text itself is never an effect. Spells, activated abilities, and triggered abilities generate effects when they resolve. }{
\i Static abilities}{ generate continuous effects.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 401. Spells
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {401.1. A card on the stac
k is a spell. As the first step of being played, the card becomes a spell and goes on the stack from the zone it was played from (usually the player\rquote s hand). (See rule 217.6, \'93Stack.\'94
) A copy of a spell is also a spell, even if it has no card associated with it. A spell stops being a spell when it resolves (see rule 413.2), is countered (see rule 414, \'93Countering Spells and Abilities\'94), or leaves the stack somehow.
\par 
\par 401.2. Each card type other than land has a corresponding spell type. For example, a played creature card is a creature spell until it resolves, is countered, or leaves the stack. An instant or sorcery spell is targeted if it uses the phrase \'93
target [something]\'94 in its spell text, where the \'93something\'94 is a phrase that describes a permanent, spell, ability, card, or player. Also, local enchantment spells target the permanent they will enchant.
\par 
\par 401.3. As the final part of an instant or sorcery spell\rquote s resolution, the card is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. As the final part of an artifact, creature, or enchantment spell\rquote 
s resolution, the card becomes a permanent and is put into the in-play zone under the control of the spell\rquote s controller. If any spell is countered, the card is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard as part of the resolution of the counteri
ng spell or ability. (See rule 413, \'93Resolving Spells and Abilities.\'94)
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 402. Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {402.1. An ability is text on a card or permanent that\rquote 
s not reminder text, flavor text, characteristic-setting text, or spell text (see rule 400.1). The result of following such an instruction or of following a spell\rquote s text is an effect. (See rule 416, \'93Effects.\'94
) Abilities can affect the cards or permanents they\rquote re on; they can also affect other cards, permanents, and/or players. Abilities can grant abilities to other cards or permanents or to the cards or permanents they\rquote 
re on; they do so when the words \'93has,\'94 \'93have,\'94 \'93gains,\'94 or \'93gain\'94 are used.
\par 
\par 402.2. Abilities can be beneficial or detrimental. For example, \'93[This creature] can\rquote t block\'94 is an ability.
\par 
\par 402.3. Text on a card stating that the card \'93is\'94 a particular type or color isn\rquote t an ability. Such statements apply no matter what zone the card is in and aren\rquote 
t removed by effects that cause a permanent to lose its abilities. This rule applies only to text that states a card\rquote s type or color, not to other characteristic-setting text.
\par 
\par 402.4. An additional cost or }{\i alternative cost}{ to play a card isn\rquote t an ability of the card. Such text is spell text.
\par 
\par 402.5. An ability isn\rquote t a spell and therefore can\rquote t be countered by anyt
hing that counters only spells. Abilities can be countered by effects that specifically counter abilities, as well as by the rules (for example, an ability with one or more targets is countered if all its targets become illegal).
\par 
\par 402.6. Once activated or triggered, an ability exists independently of its source (the card on which it\rquote s printed) as a pseudospell on the stack. Destruction or removal of the source after that time won\rquote 
t affect the ability. Note that some abilities cause a source to do something (for example, \'93Prodigal Sorcerer deals 1 damage to target creature or player\'94
) rather than the ability doing anything directly. In these cases, any spell, activated ability, or triggered ability that references information about the source will check that information when the ability resolves, or will use the source\rquote 
s last known information if it\rquote s no longer in play.
\par 
\par 402.7. A card may have several abilities. Aside from certain defined abilities that may be strung together on a single line (see rule 502, \'93Keyword Abilities\'94), each paragraph break in a card\rquote 
s text marks a separate ability. A card may also have multiple instances of the same ability. Each instance functions independently. This may or may not produce more effects than a single instance; refer to the specific ability for more information.

\par 
\par 402.8. Abilities function only while the permanent with the ability is in play unless the ability states otherwise or unless the ability can only work, trigger, or be played in a zone other than the in-play zone.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  An ability with a cost that includes \'93
discard this card from your hand\'94 can be played only if the card is in your hand.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i 
\par }{402.9. Some cards have abilities that can be played when the card is not in play. These are clearly marked (for example, \'93Play this ability only if [this card] is in your graveyard\'94). These abilities aren\rquote t of any particular permanent type
\emdash cards not in play aren\rquote t permanents. Some cards have abilities that can trigger while the card is in a zone other than the in-play zone. Such abilities specify the zone from which they trigger. They aren\rquote 
t abilities of any particular permanent type because cards not in play aren\rquote t permanents.
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \fi-274\li746\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin746\itap0 \f12\fs16\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
402.10. There are three general types of abilities: activated, triggered, and static. Mana abilities are an ability subtype. Abilities can generate }{\i one-shot effects}{ or continuous effects. Replacement effects and }{\i prevention}{
 effects are effect subtypes. An activated or triggered ability is targeted if it uses the phrase \'93target [something]\'94 in its text, where the \'93something\'94 is a phrase that describes a permanent, spell, ability, card, or player.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {403. Activated Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
403.1. An activated ability can exist in one of two places: on a permanent or on a card outside the in-play zone. An activated ability is written as \'93cost: effect.\'94 The }{\i activation cost}{ is everything before the colon (:). The ability\rquote 
s controller must pay its activation cost to play it.
\par 
\par 403.2. Only a permanent\rquote s controller (or a card\rquote s owner, for cards outside the in-play zone) can play its activated ability unless the card specifically says otherwise.
\par 
\par 403.3. If an activated ability has a restriction on its use (for example, \'93Play this ability only once each turn\'94), the restriction continues to apply to that permanent even if its controller changes.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 404. Triggered Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {404.1. A triggered ability begins with the word \'93when,\'94 \'93whenever,\'94
 or \'93at.\'94 The phrase containing one of these words is the trigger condition, which defines the trigger event. A }{\i delayed triggered ability}{ will also contain one of these three words, although that word won\rquote t usually begin the ability.

\par 
\par 404.2. Triggered abilities aren\rquote t played. Instead, a triggered ability automatically \'93triggers\'94 each time its trigger event occurs. Once an ability has triggered, it goes on the stack the next time a player would receive priority.
\par 
\par 404.3. A triggered ability may read \'93When/Whenever/At . . . , if [condition], [effect].\'94 The ability checks for the stated condition to be true when the trigger event occurs. If it is, the ability
 triggers and goes on the stack. On resolution, the ability rechecks the condition. If the condition isn\rquote t true at either of those times, the ability does nothing. This rule is referred to as the \'93intervening \lquote if\rquote  clause\'94
 rule. Note that the word \'93if\'94 has only its normal English meaning anywhere else in the text of a card; this rule only applies to an \'93if\'94 that immediately follows a trigger condition.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 405. Static Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
405.1. A static ability does something all the time rather than being activated or triggered. The ability isn\rquote t played\emdash it just \'93is.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 406. Ability Subtypes
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {406.1. Mana Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 406.1a A mana ability is either (a) an activated ability that puts mana into a player
\rquote s mana pool when it resolves or (b) a triggered ability that triggers from an activated mana ability and produces additional mana. A mana ability can generate other effects at the same time it produces mana.
\par 
\par 406.1b Spells that put mana into a player\rquote s mana pool aren\rquote t mana abilities. They\rquote re played and resolved exactly like any other spells. Triggered abilities that put mana into a player\rquote s mana pool aren\rquote 
t mana abilities if they trigger from events other than activating mana abilities. They go on the stack and resolve like any other triggered abilities.
\par 
\par 406.1c A mana ability remains a mana ability even if the game state doesn\rquote t allow it to produce mana.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  A card has an ability that reads \'93
T: Add G to your mana pool for each creature you control.\'94 This is still a mana ability even if you control no creatures, or if the card is already tapped.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 406.1d A mana ability can be activated or triggered. However, the rules for playing and resolving mana abilities differ slightly from those for playing other abilities. See rule 411, \'93Playing Mana Abilities,\'94 for details.
\par 
\par 406.1e Mana abilities are played and resolved like other abilities, but they don\rquote t go on the stack, so they can\rquote t be countered or responded to. (See rule 408.2, \'93Actions That Don\rquote t Use the Stack.\'94
) Abilities (other than mana abilities) that trigger on playing mana abilities do go on the stack, however.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 406.2. Delayed Triggered Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 406.2a An effect may create a }{\i\f28 delayed triggered ability}{\f28 
 that can do something at a later time.
\par 
\par 406.2b Delayed triggered abilities come from spells or other abilities that create them on resolution. That means a delayed triggered ability won\rquote 
t trigger until it has actually been created, even if its trigger event occurred just beforehand. Other events that happen earlier may make the trigger event impossible.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 Part of an effect reads \'93when this card leaves play,\'94
 but the card in question leaves play before the spell or ability creating the effect resolves. In this case, the delayed ability never triggers. As another example, if an effect reads \'93when this card becomes untapped\'94
 and the named card becomes untapped before the effect resolves, the ability waits for the next time that card untaps.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\f28 
\par }{\f28 406.2c A delayed ability that refers to a particular permanent still affects it even if the permanent changes characteristics.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  An ability reading, \'93At end of turn, destroy that creature\'94
 will destroy the permanent even if it\rquote s no longer a creature during the end of turn step.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\f28 
\par }{\f28 406.2d A delayed ability that refers to a particular permanent will fail if the permanent leaves play (ev
en if it returns again before the specified time). Similarly, delayed triggered abilities that apply to a card in a particular zone will fail if the card leaves that zone.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  An ability reading, \'93
At end of turn, remove this creature from the game\'94 won\rquote t do anything if the creature leaves play before the end of turn step.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 406.2e A delayed triggered ability will trigger only once\emdash the next time its trigger event occurs\emdash unless it has a stated duration, such as \'93this turn.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 407. Adding and Removing Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
407.1. Effects can add or remove abilities of permanents. If two or more effects add and remove the same ability, in general the most recent one prevails. (See rule 418.5, \'93Interaction of Continuous Effects.\'94)
\par 
\par 407.2. A permanent\rquote s characteristic set by an effect is different from an ability granted by an effect. When a permanent \'93gains\'94 or \'93has\'94
 an ability, it can be removed by another effect. If an effect defines a characteristic of the permanent (\'93[permanent] is [characteristic]\'94), it\rquote s not granting an ability. (See also rule 402.3.)
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  An effect reads, \'93Enchanted creature has \lquote 
This creature is an artifact. It\rquote s still a creature.\rquote \'94 This effect grants an ability to the creature that can be removed by other effects. Another effect reads, \'93Enchanted creature is an artifact. It\rquote s still a creature.\'94
 This effect simply defines a characteristic of the creature. It doesn\rquote t grant an ability, so effects that would cause the creature to lose its abilities wouldn\rquote t cause the enchanted creature to stop being an artifact.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 407.3. Effects that remove an ability remove all instances of it.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28 
 If a creature with flying is enchanted with Flight, it has two instances of the flying ability. A single effect that reads \'93Target creature loses flying\'94 will remove both.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 408. Timing of Spells and Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {408.1. Timing, Priority, and the Stack
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
408.1a Spells and abilities can be played only at certain times and follow a set of rules for doing so.
\par 
\par 408.1b Spells and activated abilities are played by players (if th
ey choose) using a system of priority, while other types of abilities and effects are automatically generated by the game rules. Each time a player would get priority, all applicable state-based effects resolve first as a single event (see rule 420, \'93
State-Based Effects\'94
). Then, if any new state-based effects have been generated, they resolve as a single event. This process repeats until no more applicable state-based effects are generated. Then triggered abilities are added to the stack (see rule 410, \'93Han
dling Triggered Abilities\'94
). These steps repeat in order until no further state-based effects or triggered abilities are generated. Then the player who would have received priority does so and may play a spell, ability, or land as governed by the rules for
 that phase. The game also checks for state-based effects and triggered abilities during the cleanup step (see rule 314, \'93Cleanup Step\'94). If any state-based effects resolve or abilities trigger, the active player gets priority afterward.
\par 
\par 408.1c The active
 player gets priority at the beginning of most phases and steps, after special actions and abilities that trigger at the beginning of that phase or step go on the stack. (The exceptions are the untap step and the cleanup step.) The active player also gets
 
priority after combat damage resolves. The player with priority may either play a spell or ability, or pass. If he or she plays a spell or ability, the player again receives priority; otherwise, his or her opponent receives priority. If both players pass 
i
n succession (that is, if both players pass without taking any actions in between passing), the top spell or ability on the stack resolves, then the active player receives priority. If the stack is empty when both players pass in succession, the phase or 
step ends and the next one begins.
\par 
\par 408.1d A player may play a spell or activated ability only when he or she has priority. Spells other than instants can be played only during a player\rquote s main phase, when that player has priority, and only when the stack is empty.
\par 
\par 408.1e When a spell is played, it goes on top of the stack. When an activated ability is played, a pseudospell representing it goes on the stack.
\par 
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\tx8730\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 408.1f Triggered abilities can trigger at any time, including during the playing or resolution of a 
spell or another ability. However, nothing actually happens at the time the abilities trigger. Each time a player would receive priority, a pseudospell goes on the stack for each ability that has triggered but that hasn\rquote 
t yet been put on the stack. Then the player gets priority and may play spells or abilities. (See rule 410, \'93Handling Triggered Abilities.\'94)
