\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 410.7. An ability triggers only if its trigger event actually occurs. An event that\rquote s prevented or replaced won\rquote t trigger anything.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  An ability that triggers on damage being dealt won\rquote 
t trigger if all the damage is prevented.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 410.8. Triggered abilities with a condition directly following the trigger event (for example, \'93When/Whenever/At [trigger], if [condition], [effect]\'94), check for the condition to be true as part of the trigger event; if it isn\rquote 
t, the ability doesn\rquote t trigger. The ability checks the condition again on resolution. If it\rquote s not satisfied, the ability does nothing. Note that this mirrors the check for legal targets. Note that this rule doesn\rquote 
t apply to any triggered ability with a condition elsewhere within its text.
\par 
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-386\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {410.9. Some abilities trigger when creatures block or are blocked in combat. (See rules 306\endash 311 and section 5, \'93Additional Rules.\'94
) They may trigger once or repeatedly, depending on the wording of the ability.
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 410.9a An ability that reads \'93Whenever [this creature] blocks\'94 or \'93
Whenever [this creature] becomes blocked\'94 triggers only once each combat for that creature, even if it blocks or is blocked by multiple creatures. An effect that causes the creature to become blocked (if the creature wasn\rquote t alrea
dy blocked) will also trigger such abilities.
\par 
\par 410.9b An ability that reads \'93Whenever [this creature] blocks a creature\'94 triggers once for each attacking creature the named creature blocks.
\par 
\par 410.9c An ability that reads \'93Whenever a creature blocks [this creature]\'94 triggers once for each creature that blocks the named creature. It doesn\rquote 
t trigger if the attacking creature becomes blocked by an effect rather than a blocking creature.
\par 
\par 410.9d If an ability triggers when a creature blocks or is blocked by a par
ticular number of creatures, the ability triggers only if the creature blocks or is blocked by that many creatures when the attack or block declaration is made. Effects that add or remove blockers can cause such abilities to trigger, but effects that swit
ch blockers cannot. This also applies to abilities that trigger on a creature blocking or being blocked by at least a certain number of creatures.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 410.10. Trigger events that involve cards or permanents changing zones are called \'93zone-change triggers.\'94 Man
y abilities with zone-change triggers attempt to do something to that card after it changes zones. During resolution, these abilities look for the card in the zone that it moved to. If the card is unable to be found in the zone it went to, the part of the
 
ability attempting to do something to the card will fail to do anything. The ability could be unable to find the card because the card never entered the specified zone, because it left the zone before the ability resolved, or because it is in a zone that 
is hidden from a player, such as a library or an opponent\rquote 
s hand. (This rule applies even if the card leaves the zone and returns again before the ability resolves.) The most common types of zone-change triggers are comes-into-play triggers and leaves-play triggers.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
410.10a Comes-into-play abilities trigger when a permanent enters the in-play zone. These are written, \'93When [this card] comes into play, . . . \'93 or \'93Whenever a [type] comes into play, . . .\'94
 Each time an event puts one or more permanents into play, all permanents in play (including the newcomers) are checked for any comes-into-play triggers that match the event.
\par 
\par 410.10b Continuous effects that modify characteristics of a permanent do so the moment the permanent is in play (and not before then). The permanent is never in play with its unmodified characteristics. Continuous effects don\rquote 
t apply before the permanent is in play, however (see rule 410.10e).
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  If an effect reads \'93All lands are creatures\'94
 and a land card is played, the effect makes the land card into a creature the moment it enters play, so it would trigger abilities that trigger when a creature comes into play. Conversely, if an effect reads \'93All creatures lose all abilities\'94
 and a creature card with a comes-into-play triggered ability enters play, that effect will cause it to lose its abilities the moment it enters play, so the comes-into-play ability won\rquote t trigger.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 410.10c Leaves-play abilities trigger when a permanent leaves the in-play zone. These are written as, but aren\rquote t limited to, \'93Whenever [this card] leaves play, . . .\'94 or \'93Whenever [permanent type] is put into a graveyard from play, . . . .
\'94 An ability that attempts to do something to the card that left play checks for it only in the first zone that it went to.
\par 
\par 410.10d Abilities that trigger on one or more permanents leaving play, or on a player losing control of a permanent, must be treated specially because the permanent with the ability may no longer be in play after the event. The game has to \'93
look back in time\'94 to
 determine what triggered. Each time an event removes from play or changes who controls one or more permanents, all the permanents in play just before the event (with continuous effects that existed at that time) are checked for trigger events that match 
what just left play or changed control.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  Two creatures are in play along with an artifact that has the ability 
\'93Whenever a creature is put into a graveyard from play, you gain 1 life.\'94 Someone plays a spell that destroys all artifacts, creatures, and enchantments. The artifact\rquote s ability triggers twice, even though the artifact goes to its owner
\rquote s graveyard at the same time as the creatures.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \li1260\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1260\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 \'93Leaves play\'94 triggers are zone-change triggers, even if the trigger condition doesn
\rquote t care what zone the permanent is going to. If they attempt to do something to the card that left play, they\rquote ll look for it only in the first zone that it went to after leaving play.
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 
\par 410.10e Some permanents have text that reads \'93[This permanent] comes into play with . . . ,\'94 \'93As [this permanent] comes into play . . . ,\'94 \'93[This permanent] comes into play as . . . ,\'94 or \'93[This permanent] comes into play tapped.\'94
 Such text is a static ability\emdash not a triggered ability\emdash whose effect occurs as part of the event that puts the permanent into play.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
410.11. Some triggered abilities trigger on a game state, such as a player controlling no permanents of a particular type, rather than triggering when an event occurs. These abilities trigger as soon as the game state matches the condition (even if it
\rquote s not legal to play a spell or ability at that time). These are called }{\i state triggers.}{ (Note that state triggers aren\rquote t the same as state-based effects.) A state-triggered ability doesn\rquote 
t trigger again until the pseudospell it created has resolved or been countered. Then, if the permanent with the ability is still in play and the game state still matches its trigger condition, the ability will trigger again.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  A permanent\rquote s ability reads, \'93
When your hand is empty, draw a card.\'94 If its controller plays the last card from his or her hand, the ability will trigger once and won\rquote t trigger again until it has resolved. If its controller plays a spell that reads \'93
Discard your hand, then draw the same number of cards,\'94 the ability will trigger during the spell\rquote s resolution because the player\rquote s hand was momentarily empty.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 411. Playing Mana Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
411.1. To play a mana ability, the player announces that he or she is playing it and pays the activation cost. It resolves immediately afterward and doesn\rquote t go on the stack. (See rule 408.2e.)
\par 
\par 411.2. A player may play an activated mana ability whenever he or she has priority. A player may also play one whenever a rule or effect asks for a mana payment, even in the middle of playing or resolving a spell or ability.
\par 
\par 411.3. Triggered mana abilities trigger when an activated mana ability is played. These abilities resolve immediately after the mana ability that triggered them, without waiting for priority. If an activated or triggered ability produces both mana and
 another effect, both the mana and the other effect resolve immediately.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  An enchantment reads, \'93
Whenever a player taps a land for mana, that land produces one additional mana of the same color.\'94 If a player taps lands for mana while playing a spell, the additional mana is added to the player\rquote 
s mana pool immediately and can be used to pay for the spell.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 411.3a If a triggered mana ability adds mana \'93of the same type\'94 to a player\rquote s mana pool, and the mana ability that triggered it produced more than 
one type of mana, the player to whose mana pool the mana is being added chooses which type of mana the triggered ability adds.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 412. Handling Static Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
412.1. A static ability may generate a continuous effect or a prevention or replacement effect. These effects last as long as the permanent with the static ability remains in play.
\par 
\par 412.2. Many local enchantments have static abilities that modify their enchanted permanent, but those abilities don\rquote t target that permanent. If a local enchantment is mov
ed to a different permanent, the ability stops applying to the original permanent and starts modifying the new one.
\par 
\par 412.3. Some static abilities apply while a spell is on the stack. These are often abilities that refer to countering the spell. Also, abilities that say \'93As an additional cost to play . . .\'94 and \'93You may pay [cost] rather than paying [this card]
\rquote s mana cost\'94 work while the card is a spell on the stack.
\par 
\par 412.4. Some static abilities apply while a card is in any zone that you could play it from (usually your hand). These are limited to those that read, \'93You may play [this card] . . .\'94 and \'93You can\rquote t play [this card] . . . .\'94
\par 
\par 412.5. Unlike spells and other kinds of abilities, static abilities can\rquote t use a card or permanent\rquote s last known information for purposes of determining how their effects are applied.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 413. Resolving Spells and Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
413.1. Each time both players pass in succession, the spell, ability, or combat damage on top of the stack resolves. (See rule 416, \'93Effects.\'94)
\par 
\par 413.2. Resolution of a spell or ability may involve several steps but is treated by the game as a single indivisible action. These steps are followed in the order listed below.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
413.2a If the spell or ability specifies targets, it checks whether the targets are still legal. A target that\rquote 
s removed from play, or from the zone designated by the spell or ability, is illegal. A target may also become illegal if its characteristics changed since the spell or ability was played or if an effect changed the wording of the spel
l or ability. If all targets are now illegal, the spell or ability is countered. If the spell or ability is not countered it will resolve normally, affecting only the targets that are still legal. If a target is illegal, the spell or ability can\rquote 
t perform any actions on it or make the target perform any actions. If the spell or ability needs to know information about one or more targets that are now illegal, it will use the illegal targets\rquote  current or last known information.
\par 
\par 413.2b The controller of the spell or ability follows its instructions in the order written. However, replacement effects may modify these actions. In some cases, later text on the card may modify the meaning of earlier text (for example, \'93
Destroy target creature. It can\rquote t be regenerated\'94 or \'93Counter target spell. Put it on top of its owner\rquote s library instead of into its owner\rquote s graveyard.\'94) Don\rquote 
t just apply effects step by step without thinking in these cases\emdash read the whole card and apply the rules of English to the text.
\par 
\par 413.2c If an effect offers any choices other than choices already made as part of playing the spell or ability, the player announces these while applying the effect. The player can\rquote t choose an option that\rquote 
s illegal or impossible. (For example, a player can\rquote t avoid the consequences of not taking an optional action if he or she can\rquote t meet all the immediate requirements of that action.)
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  A spell\rquote s instruction reads, \'93
You may sacrifice a creature. If you don\rquote t, you lose 4 life.\'94 A player who controls no creatures can\rquote t choose the sacrifice option.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\f28 
\par }{\f28 413.2d If an effect requires both players to make choices or take actions at the same time, the active player makes and announces his or her choices first, and then his or her opponent does (knowing the first player\rquote s choic
es). Then the actions take place simultaneously. This is called the \'93active player rule.\'94 If a player must make more than one choice at a time, he or she makes the choices in the order written, or in the order he or she chooses if the choices aren
\rquote t ordered. Then, the actions are processed simultaneously.\line 
     Some spells and abilities have multiple steps or actions, denoted by separate sentences or clauses. In these cases, the active player makes any choices required for the first action, then the nonactiv
e player makes any choices required for that action, then the first action is processed simultaneously. Then, the active player makes any choices required for the second action, then the nonactive player makes any choices required for that action, then th
at action is processed simultaneously, and so on.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  Stronghold Gambit reads, in part, \'93
Each player chooses a card in his or her hand. Then each player reveals his or her chosen card.\'94 First the active player chooses a card, then the nonactive player does so. Each player reveals the cards simultaneously.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 413.2e If an effect gives a player the option to pay mana, he or she may play mana abilities as part of the action. No other spells or abilities can be played during resolution.
\par 
\par 413.2f If an effect r
equires information from the game (such as the number of creatures in play), the answer is determined only once, when the effect is applied. The effect uses the current information of a specific permanent if that permanent is still in play, or of a specif
ic card in the stated zone; otherwise, the effect uses the last known information the card or permanent had before leaving that zone. The exception is that static abilities can\rquote 
t use last known information; see rule 412.5. If the ability text states that a permanent does something, it\rquote s the permanent as it exists (or most recently existed) that does it, not the ability.
\par 
\par 413.2g An effect that refers to characteristics of a permanent checks only for the value of the specified characteristics, regardless of any related ones the permanent may also have.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 An effect that reads \'93Destroy all black creatures\'94
 destroys a white-and-black creature, but one that reads \'93Destroy all nonblack creatures\'94 doesn\rquote t.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 413.2h A spell card is put into play from the stack under the control of the spell\rquote s controller (for permanents) or is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard from the stack (for instants and sorceries) as the final step of the spell\rquote 
s resolution.
\par 
\par 413.2i If an effect could result in a }{\i\f28 tie,}{\f28  the text of the spell or ability that created the effect will specify what to do in the event of a tie. The }{\b\f28 Magic}{\f28  game has no default for ties.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 414. Countering Spells and Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {414.1. To counter a spell is to move the spell card from the stack to its owner
\rquote s graveyard. Countering a copy of a spell removes the copy from the stack. Countering an ability removes its pseudospell from the stack. Spells and abilities that are countered don\rquote t resolve and none of their effects occur.
\par 
\par 414.2. The player who played the countered spell or ability doesn\rquote t get a \'93refund\'94 of any costs that were paid.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 415. Editing a Spell or Ability
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {415.1. A few effects can \'93edit\'94
 a spell or ability after it goes on the stack, changing its target, rules text, or other characteristics.
\par 
\par 415.2. The target of a spell or ability can change only to another legal target. If the new target is illegal when the change resolves, the original target is unchanged.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
415.2a Modal spells may have different targeting requirements for each mode. Changing a spell or ability\rquote s target can\rquote t change its mode.
\par 
\par 415.2b The word \'93you\'94 in a card\rquote s text isn\rquote t a target. If a spell affects only its controller, its target can\rquote t be changed.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 415.3. If an effect edits any characteristics of a spell that becomes a permanent, the effect continues to apply to the permanent when the spell resolves.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28 
 If an effect changes a black creature spell to white, the creature is white when it comes into play and remains white for the duration of the effect changing its color.
\par }{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {415.4. An effect that
 changes the text of a spell or permanent only changes words that are of the correct type (for example, a }{\b Magic }{
color word being used as a color word, a land type word used as a land type, or a creature type word used as a creature type). The effect can\rquote t 
change a proper noun, such as a card name, even if that proper noun contains a word or a series of letters that is the same as a }{\b Magic}{ color word, basic land type, or creature type.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28      Spells and abilities that create creature tokens use creature types t
o define both the creature types and the names of the tokens. These words can be changed, because they are being used as creature types, even though they\rquote 
re also being used as names. Once a token has been created, it has its creature type and name printed on it. The creature type of a creature token in play can be changed, but its name can\rquote t.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 416. Effects
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
416.1. When a spell or ability resolves, it may create one or more effects. There are three main types: one-shot effects, continuous effects, and replac
ement and prevention effects. Effects of a fourth category, state-based effects, are generated by specific states of the game.
\par 
\par 416.2. Effects apply only to permanents unless the instruction\rquote s text states otherwise or they clearly can apply only to cards in one or more other zones.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  An effect that changes all lands to creatures won\rquote 
t alter land cards in the players\rquote  graveyards.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\sl-220\slmult0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i 
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {416.3. If an effect attempts to do something impossible, it does only as much as possible.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  If a player is holding only one card, an effect that reads \'93
Discard two cards\'94 causes him or her to discard only that card. If an effect moves cards out of the library (as opposed to drawing), it moves as many as possible.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 417. One-Shot Effects
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {417.1. A one-shot effect does something just once and doesn\rquote 
t have a duration. Examples include damage dealing, destruction of permanents, and moving cards between zones.
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\sl-220\slmult0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {417.2. Some one-shot effects instruct a player to do something later in the game (usually at a specific time) rathe
r than when they resolve. This kind of effect actually creates a new ability that waits to be triggered. (See rule 406.2, \'93Delayed Triggered Abilities.\'94)
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 418. Continuous Effects
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {418.1. A continuous effect modifies characteristics of cards and/or permanen
ts or modifies the rules of the game for a fixed or indefinite period. A continuous effect may be generated by the resolution of a spell or ability or by a static ability of a permanent.
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\sl-220\slmult0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {418.2. Continuous effects that modify characteristics of permanents do so simultaneously with the permanent coming into play. They don\rquote 
t wait until the permanent is in play and then change it. Because such effects apply as the permanent comes into play, apply them before determining whether the permanent will cause an ability to trigger when it comes into play.
\par 
\par 418.3. Continuous Effects from Spells or Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
418.3a A continuous effect generated by the resolution of a spell or ability lasts as long as stated by the spell or ability creating it (such as \'93until end of turn\'94). If no duration is stated, it lasts until the end of the game.
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\sl-220\slmult0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 
418.3b Continuous effects from spells, activated abilities, and triggered abilities that modify the characteristics or change the controller of one or more cards and/or permanents don\rquote t affect cards and/or permanents that weren\rquote 
t affected when the continuous effect began. Note that these work differently than continuous effects from static abilities. Continuous effects that don\rquote t modify characteristics or change the controller of cards and/
or permanents modify the rules of the game, so they can}{\i\f28  }{\f28 affect cards and/or permanents that weren\rquote t affected when the continuous effect began.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  An effect that reads \'93All white creatures get +1/+1 until end of turn
\'94 gives the bonus to all permanents that are white creatures when the spell or ability resolves\emdash even if they change color later\emdash and doesn\rquote t affect those that come into play or turn white afterward.
\par }{\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  An effect that reads \'93Prevent all damage creatures would deal this turn\'94 doesn\rquote t modify any card\rquote s or permanent\rquote s characteristics, so it\rquote 
s modifying the rules of the game. That means the effect will apply even to creatures that weren\rquote t in play when the continuous effect began. It also affects permanents that become creatures later in the turn.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\f28 
\par }{\f28 418.3c If the spell or ability creating a continuous effect contains a variable, the value of that variable is determined only once, on resolution. See rule 413.2f.
\par }{\i\f28 
\par }{\f28 418.3d Some effects from activated or triggered abilities have durations worded \'93as long as . . . .\'94 If the \'93as long as\'94
 duration ends between the end of announcing the activated ability or putting the triggered ability onto the stack and the moment when the effect would first be applied, the effect does nothing. It doesn\rquote t start and imm
ediately stop again, and it doesn\rquote t last forever.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  Endoskeleton is an artifact with an activated ability that reads \'93}{
\i0\f28 2, T:}{\f28  Target creature gets +0/+3 as long as Endoskeleton remains tapped.\'94 If you play this ability and then Endoskeleton becomes untapped before the ability resolves, it does nothing, because its duration\emdash remaining tapped\emdash 
was over before the effect began.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {418.4. Continuous Effects from Static Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 418.4a A continuous effect generated by a static ability isn\rquote t \'93locked in
\'94; it applies at any given moment to whatever its text indicates.
\par 
\par 418.4b The effect applies at all times that the permanent generating it is in play or the card generating it is in the appropriate zone.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  A permanent with the static ability \'93All white creatures get +1/+1
\'94 generates an effect that continuously gives +1/+1 to each white creature in play. If a creature becomes white, it gets this bonus; a creature that stops being white loses it. A creature spell that would normally create a 1/1 white creature
 instead creates a 2/2 white creature. The creature doesn\rquote t come into play as 1/1 and then change to 2/2.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 418.5. Interaction of Continuous Effects
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
418.5a Sometimes the results of one effect determine whether another effect applies or what it does. For example, one effect might read, \'93All white creatures get +1/+1\'94 and another, \'93Enchanted creature is white.\'94
\par 
\par 418.5b An effect is said to \'93depend on\'94 another if applying the other would change the text or the existence of the first effect, what it applies to,
 or what it does to any of the things it applies to. Otherwise, the effect is considered to be independent of the first effect.
\par 
\par 418.5c Whenever one effect depends on another, the independent one is applied first. If several dependent effects form a loop, or if none depends on another, they\rquote re applied in \'93timestamp order.\'94 A card or permanent\rquote 
s timestamp is the time it entered the zone it\rquote s currently in, with two exceptions: (1) If two or more cards or permanents enter a zone (or zones) simultaneously, the 
active player determines their timestamp order at the time they enter that zone, but a local enchantment must be timestamped after what it enchants. (2) Whenever a local enchantment becomes attached to a permanent, the enchantment receives a new timestamp
.
 Continuous effects generated by static abilities have the same timestamp as the card or permanent that generated them. Continuous effects generated by the resolution of a spell or ability receive a timestamp when the spell or ability creating them resolv
es.
\par 
\par 418.5d A continuous effect can override another.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  Two enchantments are played on the same creature: \'93
Enchanted creature gains flying\'94 and \'93Enchanted creature loses flying.\'94 Neither of these depends on the other, since nothing changes what they affect or what they\rquote 
re doing to it. Applying them in timestamp order means the one that was generated last \'93wins.\'94 It\rquote s irrelevant whether an effect is temporary (such as \'93Target creature loses flying until end of turn\'94) or global (such as \'93
All creatures lose flying\'94).
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 418.5e The value of a permanent\rquote 
s characteristic is determined by starting with the printed or token value, then applying copy effects (see rule 503, \'93Copying Spells and Abilities\'94), then applying continuous effects generated by type-changin
g abilities, then applying any power or toughness changes due to counters, and then applying all other continuous effects.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 419. Replacement and Prevention Effects
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
419.1. Replacement and prevention effects are continuous effects that watch for a particula
r event to happen and then completely or partially replace that event. (A prevention effect replaces an event with nothing or with a lessened version of the event.) These effects act like \'93shields\'94 around whatever they\rquote 
re affecting. All replacement effects use the word \'93instead\'94 to indicate what events will be replaced with other events, and prevention effects use \'93prevent\'94 to indicate what events will not occur. Abilities that contain \'93instead\'94 or 
\'93prevent\'94 generate replacement or prevention effects, respectively.
\par 
\par 419.2. Replacement and prevention effects apply continuously as events happen\emdash they aren\rquote t locked in ahead of time.
\par 
\par 419.3. There are no special restrictions on playing a spell or ability that generates a replacement or prevention effect. Such effects last until they\rquote re used up or their duration has expired.
\par 
\par 419.4. Replacement or prevention effects must exist before the appropriate event occurs\emdash they can\rquote t \'93go back in time\'94 and change something that\rquote s already happened. Usually spells and abilities 
that generate these effects are played in }{\i response}{ to whatever would produce the event and thus resolve before that event would occur.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28 
 A player can play a regeneration ability in response to a spell that would destroy a creature he or she controls.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 419.5. If an event is prevented or replaced, it never happens. A modified event occurs instead, which may in turn trigger abilities. Note that the modified event may contain instructions that can\rquote 
t be carried out, in which case the player simply ignores the impossible instruction. If a source would deal 0 damage, it does not deal damage at all. That means abilities that trigger on damage being dealt won\rquote 
t trigger. It also means that replacement effects that increase damage dealt have no event to replace when 0 damage is dealt, so they have no effect. Some abilities read, \'93Whenever [X], you may [Y]. If you do, [Z].\'94 The \'93if you do\'94
 clause refers to doing any part of the event Y. If Y is replaced entirely or in part by a different event, the \'93if you do\'94 clause refers to the event that replaced Y.
\par 
\par 419.6. Replacement Effects
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 419.6a A replacement effect doesn\rquote 
t invoke itself repeatedly and gets only one opportunity for each event.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  A player controls two permanents, each with an ability that reads \'93
Instead of dealing their normal damage, creatures you control deal double that damage.\'94 A creature that normally deals 1 damage will deal 4 damage\emdash not just 2, and not an infinite amount.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 419.6b Regeneration is a destruction-replacement effect. The key word \'93instead\'94 doesn\rquote t appear on the card but is implicit in its definition. \'93Regenerate [permanent]\'94 means \'93
The next time [permanent] would be destroyed this turn, instead remove all damage from it, tap it, and (if it\rquote s in combat) remove it from combat.\'94 Note that if destruction is caused by }{\i\f28 lethal damage,}{\f28 
 any abilities that trigger from that damage being dealt still trigger even if the permanent regenerates.
\par 
\par 419.6c Some effects replace damage dealt to one creature or player with the same damage dealt to another creature or player; such effects are called \'93redirection\'94
 effects. If either creature is no longer in play or is no longer a creature when the damage would be redirected, the effect does nothing. Likewise, if either player is no longer in the game, the effect does nothing.
\par 
\par 419.6d }{\f28\cgrid0 Some spells and abilities replace part or all of their own effect(s) when they resolve. Such effects are called \'93self-replacement effects.\'94 When applying replacement effects to an event, apply self-replacement effects first, the
n apply other replacement effects.}{\f28 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {419.7. Prevention Effects
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 419.7a Prevention effects usually apply to damage that would be dealt.
\par 
\par 419.7b Some prevention effects refer to a specific amount of damage\emdash for example, \'93Prevent the next 3 damage to target creature or player this turn.\'94 These work like ablative shields. Each 1 damage that would be dealt to the \'93shielded\'94
 creature or player is prevented. Preventing 1 damage reduces the remaining shield by 1. If damage would be dealt to the shielded creature or p
layer by two or more sources at the same time, the player or the controller of the creature can choose which damage the shield prevents first. Once the shield has been reduced to 0, any remaining damage is dealt normally. Such effects count only the amoun
t of damage; the number of events or sources dealing it doesn\rquote t matter.
\par 
\par 419.7c Some prevention effects apply to damage from a specified source\emdash for example, \'93The next time a red source of your choice would deal damage to you this turn, prevent that damage.\'94
 The source is chosen when the spell or ability resolves. If an effect requires a player to choose a source, he or she may choose either a permanent or a spell on the stack (including one that creates a permanent) or any card or permanent referred to by a
 spell or pseudospell on the stack. If the player chooses a permanent or a permanent spell, the prevention will apply to the next damage from that permanent or the permanent resulting from the spell, regardless of whether it\rquote 
s from one of that permanent\rquote s abilities or combat damage dealt by it. It\rquote s possible for the source to be out of play by the time the spell or ability resolves.\line 
     Some abilities that generate prevention effects can affect damage only from a source with certain characteristics, such as a creature or a source of a particular color. When the chosen source would deal damage, a prevention \'93shield\'94
 with this type of restriction rechecks the source\rquote s characteristics. If the characteristics no longer match, the damage isn\rquote t prevented. If for any reason the shield prevents no damage, the shield isn\rquote t used up.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {419.8. Interaction of Replacement or Prevention Effects
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
419.8a If two or more replacement or prevention effects are attempting to modify the way an event affects a permanent or player, the affected permanent\rquote 
s controller or the affected player chooses one to apply to that permanent or player. Then the other applies if it is still appropriate. If one or more of the applicable replacement effects is a \'93self-replacement effect\'94 (see rule 419.
6d), that effect is applied before any other replacement effects.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  Two cards are in play. One is an enchantment that reads \'93
If a card would be put into a graveyard, instead remove it from the game,\'94 and the other is a creature that reads \'93If [this card] would be put into a graveyard, instead shuffle it into its owner\rquote s library.\'94
 The controller of the creature that would be destroyed decides which replacement to apply first; the other does nothing.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 419.8b A replacement effect can become applicable to an event as the result of another replacement effect that modifies the event.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  One effect reads, \'93
For each 1 life you would gain, instead draw a card,\'94 and another reads, \'93Instead of drawing a card, return target card from your graveyard to your hand.\'94
 Both effects combine (regardless of the order they came into play): Instead of gaining 1 life, the player puts a card from his or her graveyard into his or her hand.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 420. State-Based Effects
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {420.1. State-based effects are a special category that a
pplies only to those conditions listed below. Abilities that watch for a specified game state are triggered abilities. (See rule 410.8.)
\par 
\par 420.2. State-based effects are always active and are not controlled by either player.
\par 
\par 420.3. Whenever a player would get priority to play a spell or ability (see rule 408, \'93Timing of Spells and Abilities\'94
), the game checks for any of the listed conditions for state-based effects. All applicable effects resolve as a single event, then the check is repeated. Once no more s
tate-based effects have been generated, triggered abilities go on the stack, then the appropriate player gets priority. This check is also made during the cleanup step (see rule 314); if any of the listed conditions apply, the active player receives prior
ity.
\par 
\par 420.4. Unlike triggered abilities, state-based effects pay no attention to what happens during the resolution of a spell or ability.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  A player controls a creature with the ability \'93This creature\rquote 
s power and toughness are each equal to the number of cards in your hand\'94 and plays a spell whose effect is \'93Discard your hand, then draw seven cards.\'94 The creature will temporarily have toughness 0 in the middle of the spell\rquote 
s resolution but will be back up to toughness 7 when the spell finishes resolv
ing. Thus the creature will survive when state-based effects are checked. In contrast, an ability that triggers when the player has no cards in hand goes on the stack after the spell resolves, because its trigger event happened during resolution.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i 
\par }{420.5. The state-based effects are as follows:
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 420.5a A player with 0 life or less loses the game.
\par 
\par 420.5b A creature with toughness 0 or less is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. Regeneration can\rquote t replace this event.
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\sl-220\slmult0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 420.5c A creature with lethal damage is destroyed. Lethal damage is an amount of damage greater than 0 and greater than or equal to a creature\rquote 
s toughness. Regeneration does replace this event.
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\sl-220\slmult0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 420.5d A local enchantment that enchants an illegal or nonexistent permanent is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard.
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\sl-220\slmult0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 
420.5e If two or more Legends or legendary permanents with the same name are in play, all except the one that has been a Legend or legendary permanent with that name the longest are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards. This is called \'93
the Legend rule.\'94 In the event of a tie, each Legend or legendary permanent with the same name is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. (If two permanents have the same name but only one is a Legend or is legendary, this rule doesn\rquote t apply.)

\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\sl-220\slmult0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 
\par }\pard \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 {\f28 420.5f A token in a zone other than the in-play zone ceases to exist.
\par 
\par 420.5g A player who was required to draw more cards than were in his or her library loses the game.
\par 
\par 420.5h A player with ten or more poison counters loses the game.
\par 
\par 420.5i If two or more enchant worlds are in play, all except the one that has been an enchant world for the shortest amount of time are put into their owners\rquote 
 graveyards. In the event of a tie for the shortest amount of time, all are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards.
\par 
\par 420.5j A copy of a spell in a zone other than the stack ceases to exist.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 421. Handling \'93Infinite\'94 Loops
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
421.1. Occasionally the game can get into a state in which a set of actions could be repeated forever. The \'93}{\i infinity rule\'94}{ governs how to break such loops.
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\sl-240\slmult0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {421.2. If the loop contains one 
or more optional actions and one player controls them all, that player chooses a number. The loop is treated as repeating that many times or until the other player intervenes, whichever comes first.
\par 
\par 421.3. If the loop contains at least one optional action
 controlled by each player and actions by both players are required to continue the loop, the active player chooses a number. The nonactive player then has two choices. He or she can choose a lower number, in which case the loop continues that number of t
imes plus whatever fraction is necessary for the active player to \'93have the last word.\'94
 Or he or she can agree to the number the active player chose, in which case the loop continues that number of times plus whatever fraction is necessary for the nonactive player to \'93have the last word.\'94 (Note that either fraction may be zero.)

\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  One player controls a creature with the }{\f28\cf1 ability \'93
0: [This creature] gains flying.\'94 Another player controls a permanent with the ability \'930: Target creature loses flying.\'94 The \'93infinity rule\'94
 ensures that regardless of which player initiated the gain/lose flying ability, the nonactive player will always}{\f28  have the final choice and therefore be able to determine whether the creature has flying. (Note that this assumes that the fi
rst player attempted to give the creature flying at least once.)}{\f28\cf13 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 421.4. If the loop contains only mandatory actions, the game ends in a draw. (See rule 102.6.)
\par 
\par 421.5. If the loop contains at least one optional action controlled by each player and these actions don\rquote 
t depend on one another, the active player chooses a number. The nonactive player can either agree to that number or choose a higher number. Note that this rule applies even if the actions could exist in separate loops rather than in a single loop.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 422. Handling Illegal Actions
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {422.1. If a player realizes that he or she can\rquote 
t legally take an action after starting to do so, the entire action is reversed and any payments already made are canceled. No abilities trigger and no effects apply as a re
sult of an undone action. If the action was playing a spell, the spell card returns to the zone it came from. The player may also reverse any legal mana abilities played while making the illegal play, unless mana from them or from any triggered mana abili
ties they triggered was spent on another mana ability that wasn\rquote 
t reversed. Players may not reverse actions that moved cards to a library or from a library to any zone other than the stack. Players may not reverse actions that involved a random choice or random zone change.}{\cf13 
\par }{
\par 422.2. When reversing illegal spells and abilities, the player who had priority retains it and may take another action or pass. The player may redo the reversed action in a legal way or take any other action allowed by the rules.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par }{\f28 \page }{\f28\fs22 5. Additional Rules
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 500. Legal Attacks and Blocks
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
500.1. Some abilities and continuous effects restrict declaring attackers or blockers in combat or require certain creatures to be declared as attackers or blockers. (See rule 308, \'93Declare Attackers Step,\'94 and rule 309, \'93Declare Blockers Step.
\'94) A restriction is an effect which says that a creature can\rquote t block (or attack) or that it can\rquote t block (or attack) unless some condition is met. A requirement is an effect which says that a creature must block (or attack
) or that it must block (or attack) if some condition is met.
\par 
\par }\pard \s17\ql \fi-29\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 {500.2. As part of declaring attackers, the active player checks each creature he or she controls to see whether it must attack, can\rquote 
t attack, or has some other attacking restriction or requirem
ent. If such a restriction or requirement conflicts with the proposed attack, the attack is illegal, and the active player must then propose another set of attacking creatures. (Tapped creatures and creatures with unpaid costs to attack are exempt from ef
fects that would require them to attack.)
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  A player controls two creatures, each with a restriction that states 
\'93[This creature] can\rquote t attack alone.\'94 It\rquote s legal to declare both as attackers.
\par }{\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  A player controls two creatures: one that \'93attacks if able\'94 and one with no abilities. An effect states, \'93No more than one creature may attack each turn.\'94 The only legal attack is for just the creature that \'93
attacks if able\'94 to attack. It\rquote s illegal to attack with the other creature, attack with both, or attack with neither.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 500.3. As part of declaring blockers, the defending player checks each creature he or she controls to see whether it must block, can\rquote t block, or has some other blocking restriction or requirement. If such a restriction or requirement 
conflicts with the proposed set of blocking creatures, the block is illegal, and the defending player must then propose another set of blocking creatures. (Creatures with unpaid costs to block are exempt from effects that would require them to block.)

\par 
\par 500.4. A restriction conflicts with a proposed set of attackers or blockers if it isn\rquote t being followed. A requirement conflicts with a proposed set of attackers or blockers if it isn\rquote 
t being followed and 1) the requirement could be obeyed without conflicting with a restriction that the set does obey and 2) obeying the requirement will increase the number of requirements that the set obeys.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {500.5. A requirement on one creature can\rquote 
t be combined with a restriction to produce such a requirement on another creature.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  A player controls one creature that \'93blocks if able\'94
 and another creature with no abilities. An effect states, \'93Creatures can't be blocked except by two or more creatures.\'94 The creature with no abilities isn\rquote t required to block. It\rquote s legal to 
declare both creatures as blockers, or to declare neither creature as a blocker, but illegal to block with only one of the two.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 501. Evasion Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {501.1. }{\i Evasion}{ }{\i abilities}{
 restrict what can block an attacking creature. These are static abilities that modify the declare blockers step of combat.
\par 
\par 501.2. Evasion abilities are cumulative.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example}{\f28 : A Wall without flying can\rquote 
t block a creature that can be blocked only by Walls and by creatures with flying.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 501.3. Some creatures have abilities that restrict how they can block. As with evasion abilities, these modify only the rules for the declare blockers step of combat. (If a creature gains an evasion ability after a legal block has been declared, it doesn
\rquote t affect that block.)
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 502. Keyword Abilities
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {502.1. Most creature abilities describe exactly what they do in the card\rquote 
s rules text. Some, though, are very common or would require too much space to define on the card. In these cases, the card lists only the name of the ability as a \'93keyword\'94; sometimes reminder text summarizes the game rule.
\par 
\par 502.2. First Strike
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.2a }{\i\f28 First strike}{\f28 
 is a static ability that modifies the rules for the combat damage step.
\par 
\par 502.2b During the combat damage step, if at least one attacking or blocking creature has first strike or double strike (see rule 502.28), creatures without first strike or double strike don\rquote 
t assign combat damage. Instead of proceeding to end of combat, the phase gets a second combat damage step to handle the remaining creatures.
\par 
\par 502.2c Adding or removing first strike after the first combat damage step won\rquote t prevent a creature from dealing combat damage or allow it to deal combat damage twice.
\par 
\par 502.2d Multiple instances of first strike on the same creature are redundant.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 502.3. Flanking
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.3a }{\i\f28 Flanking}{\f28  is
 a triggered ability that triggers during the declare blockers step.
\par 
\par 502.3b Whenever a creature with flanking is blocked by a creature without flanking, the blocking creature gets -1/-1 until end of turn.
\par 
\par 502.3c If a creature has multiple instances of flanking, each triggers separately.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 502.4. Flying
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.4a }{\i\f28 Flying}{\f28  is an evasion ability.
\par 
\par 502.4b A creature with flying can\rquote t be blocked by creatures without flying. A creature with flying can block a creature with or without flying.
\par 
\par 502.4c Multiple instances of flying on the same creature are redundant.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 502.5. Haste
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.5a }{\i\f28 Haste}{\f28  is a static ability.
\par 
\par 502.5b A creature with haste can attack or use activated abilities whose cost includes the tap symbol even if it hasn\rquote t been controlled by its controller continuously since the beginning of his or her most recent turn.
\par 
\par 502.5c Multiple instances of haste on the same creature are redundant.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 502.6. Landwalk
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.6a }{\i\f28 Landwalk}{\f28  and }{\i\f28 snow-covered landwalk}{\f28 
 are generic terms; a card\rquote s rules text usually names a specific type of land (such as in \'93islandwalk\'94 or \'93snow-covered swampwalk\'94).
\par 
\par 502.6b Landwalk and snow-covered landwalk are evasion abilities. A creature with landwalk is unblockable as long as the defending player controls at least one land of the specified type
. A creature with snow-covered landwalk is unblockable as long as the defending player controls at least one land of the specified type that has }{\i\f28 snow-covered.}{\f28 
\par 
\par 502.6c Snow-covered landwalk is a special type of landwalk. If a player is allowed to choose any
 landwalk ability, that player may choose a snow-covered landwalk ability. If an effect causes a permanent to lose all landwalk abilities, snow-covered landwalk abilities are removed as well.
\par 
\par 502.6d Landwalk or snow-covered landwalk abilities don\rquote t \'93cancel\'94 one another.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 If a player controls a snow-covered forest, that player can\rquote 
t block an attacking creature with snow-covered forestwalk even if he or she also controls a creature with snow-covered forestwalk.}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 502.6e Multiple instances of the same type of landwalk or snow-covered landwalk on the same creature are redundant.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 502.7. Protection
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.7a }{\i\f28 Protection}{\f28  is a static ability, written \'93
Protection from [quality].\'94 This quality is usually a color (as in \'93protection from black\'94) but can be any characteristic. If the quality is a type, the protection applies to sources that are permanents with that type and to any sources that aren
\rquote t in play that are of that type.
\par 
\par 502.7b A permanent with protection can\rquote t be targeted by spells with the stated quality, can\rquote t be targeted by abilities from a source with the stated quality, and can\rquote 
t be enchanted by enchantments that have the stated quality. Such enchantments enchanting the permanent with protection will be put into their owners\rquote  graveyards as a state-ba
sed effect. In addition, any damage that would be dealt to it from sources having that quality is prevented. If it attacks, it can\rquote t be blocked by creatures having that quality.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.7c Multiple instances of protection from the same quality on the same per
manent are redundant.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 502.8. Shadow
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.8a }{\i\f28 Shadow}{\f28  is an evasion ability.
\par 
\par 502.8b A creature with shadow can\rquote t be blocked by creatures without shadow, and a creature without shadow can\rquote t be blocked by creatures with shadow.
\par 
\par 502.8c Multiple instances of shadow on the same creature are redundant.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 502.9. Trample
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.9a }{\i\f28 Trample}{\f28 
 is a static ability that modifies the rules for assigning an attacking creature\rquote s combat damage. A creature with trample has no special abilities when blocking or dealing noncombat damage.
\par 
\par 502.9b The controller of an attacking creature with trample first assigns damage to the creature(s) blocking it. If all those blocking creatures are assigned lethal damage, any remaining damage is assigned as its controller chooses among the blocki
ng creatures and the defending player. When checking for assigned lethal damage, take into account damage already on the creature and damage from other creatures that is to be assigned at the same time (see rule 502.9f). The controller need not assign let
hal damage to all blocking creatures but in that case can\rquote t assign any damage to the defending player.
\par 
\par 502.9c If all the creatures blocking an attacking creature with trample are removed from combat before the combat damage step, all its damage is assigned to the defending player.
\par 
\par 502.9d Ignore this rule.
\par 
\par 502.9e Assigning damage from a creature with trample considers only the actual toughness of a blocking creature, not any abilities or effects that might change the final amount of damage dealt.
\par 
\par 502.9f When there are several attacking creatures, it\rquote s legal to assign damage from those without trample so as to maximize the damage of those with trample.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28 
 A 2/2 creature with an ability that enables it to block multiple attackers blocks two attackers: 
a 1/1 with no special abilities a 3/3 with trample. The active player could assign 1 damage from the first attacker and 1 damage from the second to the blocking creature, and 2 damage to the defending player from the creature with trample.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\f28 
\par }{\f28 502.9g Multiple instances of trample on the same creature are redundant.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {502.10. Banding
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 502.10a }{\i\f28 Banding}{\f28  is a static ability that modifies the rules for declaring attackers, declaring blockers, and assigning combat damage.
\par 
\par 502.10b As a player declares attackers, he or she may declare that any number of those creatures with banding, and up to one of those creatures without banding, are all in a \'93band.\'94 (Defending players can\rquote 
t declare bands but may use banding in a different way; see rule 502.10h.)
\par 
\par 502.10c A player may declare as many attacking bands as he or she wants, but each creature may be a member of only one of them.
\par 
\par 502.10d Once an attacking band has been announced, it lasts for the rest of combat, even if something later removes the banding ability from one or more creatures. However, creatures in a band that are removed from combat are also removed from the band.

\par 
\par 502.10e If an attacking creature becomes blocked by a creature, each other creature in the same band as the attacking creature becomes blocked by that same blocking creature.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 
A player attacks with a band consisting of a creature with flying and a creature with swampwalk. The defending player, who controls a swamp, can block the flying creature if able. If he or she does, then the creature wit
h swampwalk will also become blocked by the blocking creature(s).}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 502.10f Banding doesn\rquote t cause attacking creatures to share abilities, nor does it remove any abilities. The attacking creatures in a band are separate permanents.
\par 
\par 502.10g If one member of a band would become blocked as the result of a spell or ability, the entire band becomes blocked.
\par 
\par 502.10h A player who controls a banding creature chooses how combat damage is assigned by creatures blocking or blocked by that creature. If the creature had
 banding when it attacked or blocked, but the ability was removed before the combat damage step, damage is assigned normally.
\par 
\par 502.10i Multiple instances of banding on the same creature are redundant.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {502.11. Bands with Other
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 502.11a }{\i\f28 Bands with other}{\f28  is a special form of banding. If an effect causes a permanent to lose banding, the permanent loses all bands with other abilities as well.
\par 
\par 502.11b An attacking creature with \'93bands with other [creature type]\'94 can form an attacking band with other creatures that have the same \'93bands with other [creature type]\'94
 ability. Creatures with banding can also join this band, but creatures without banding can\rquote t. The creatures in this band don\rquote t have to have the creature type specified in the \'93bands with other [creature type]\'94
 ability. Blocking this band follows the same general rules as for banding.
\par 
\par 502.11c If a creature is blocked by at least two creatures with the same \'93bands with other [creature type]\'94 ability, the defending player chooses how the attacking creature\rquote 
s damage is assigned. Similarly, if a creature blocks at least two attacking creatures with the same \'93bands with other [creature type]\'94 ability, the attacking player chooses how the blocking creature\rquote s damage is assigned.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {502.12. Rampage
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.12a }{\i\f28 Rampage}{\f28  is a triggered ability. \'93Rampage [X]\'94 means 
\'93Whenever this creature becomes blocked by two or more creatures, it gets +X/+X until end of turn for each creature blocking it beyond the first.\'94
\par 
\par 502.12b The rampage bonus is calculated only once per combat, when the triggered ability resolves. Adding or removing blockers later in combat won\rquote t change the bonus.
\par 
\par 502.12c If a creature has multiple instances of rampage, each triggers separately.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {502.13. Cumulative Upkeep
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.13a }{\i\f28 Cumulative upkeep}{\f28  is a triggered 
ability that imposes an increasing cost on a permanent. The phrase \'93Cumulative upkeep [cost]\'94 means \'93
At the beginning of your upkeep, put an age counter on this permanent, then sacrifice this permanent unless you pay [cost] for each age counter on it.\'94
\par 
\par 50
2.13b If a permanent has multiple instances of cumulative upkeep, each triggers separately. However, the age counters are not linked to any particular ability; each cumulative upkeep ability will count the total number of age counters on the permanent at 
the time that ability resolves.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 A creature has two instances of \'93Cumulative upkeep\emdash Pay 1 life.
\'94 The creature currently has no counters but both cumulative upkeep abilities trigger. When the first ability resolves, the controller adds a counter and 
then chooses to pay 1 life. When the second ability resolves, the controller adds another counter and then chooses to pay an additional 2 life.}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 502.14. Snow-Covered
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.14a Snow-covered is an ability that doesn\rquote 
t do anything in its own right; it\rquote s simply a keyword that other cards look for. When a card refers to a \'93snow-covered land,\'94 it means a land with the snow-covered ability. When a card refers to a \'93snow-covered forest,\'94
 it means a forest with the snow-covered ability, and so on.
\par 
\par 502.14b Five snow-covered lands were printed in the }{\i\f28 Ice Age\'99}{\f28 
 expansion. Their names are Snow-Covered Plains, Snow-Covered Island, Snow-Covered Swamp, Snow-Covered Mountain, and Snow-Covered Forest. These lands are basic lands, even though they have a different name and they have the snow-covered ability.
\par 
\par 502.14c Some effects can add or remove the snow-covered ability. This doesn\rquote t change the existing name of the land. For example, a card named Snow-Covered Forest is named \'93Snow-Covered Forest,\'94 while a forest that has been 
granted the snow-covered ability is still named \'93Forest.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 502.15. Phasing
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 502.15a Phasing is a static ability that modifies the rules of the untap step.
\par 
\par 502.15b During each player\rquote s untap step, before that player untaps his or her permanents, all permanents with phasing the player controls phase out. Simultaneously, all permanents that had phased out under that player\rquote 
s control phase in. (See rule 217.8, \'93Phased-Out,\'94 and rule 302.3.)
\par 
\par 502.15c If a spell or ability causes a player to skip his or her untap step, the phasing event simply doesn\rquote t occur that turn.
\par 
\par 502.15d Permanents phasing in don\rquote t trigger any comes-into-play abilities, and effects that modify how a permanent comes into play are ignored. Abilities and effects that specifically mention phasi
ng can modify or trigger on this event, however. Permanents phasing out trigger leaves-play abilities as usual. (Because no player receives priority during the untap step, any abilities triggering off of the phasing event won\rquote 
t go onto the stack until the upkeep step begins.)
\par 
\par 502.15e When a permanent phases out, all damage dealt to it is removed.
\par 
\par 502.15f A card that returns to play from the phased-out zone is in some respects considered the same permanent it was when it left. This is an exception to rule 217.8, which stipulates that a permanent \'93forgets\'94
 its previous existence when it changes zones.
\par 
\par 502.15g Effects with limited duration and delayed triggered abilities that specifically reference a permanent will be unable to further affect that permanent 
if it phases out. However, other effects that reference the permanent (including effects with unlimited duration) can affect the permanent when it returns to play.
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 
A creature is affected by Giant Growth and then phases out during the same turn. If the creature phases back in somehow before the turn is over, it won\rquote t get the +3/+3 bonus from the Giant Growth because its effect has a limited duration.}{\b\f28 

\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 502.15h Phased-out cards \'93remember\'94 their past histories and will return to play in the same state. They \'93remember\'94
 any counters they had on them, any choices made when they first came into play, and whether they were tapped or untapped when they left play. They also \'93remember\'94 who controlled them when they phased out, although they may phase in under t
he control of a different player if a control effect with limited duration has expired. 
\par }\pard\plain \s22\ql \li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 Diseased Vermin reads, in part, \'93
At the beginning of your upkeep, Diseased Vermin deals X damage to target opponent previously dealt damage by it, where X is the number of infection counters on it.\'94 If Diseased Vermin phases out, it \'93remembers\'94
 how many counters it has and also which opponents it has previously damaged. When it phases back in, it will still be able to target those opponents with its upkeep-triggered ability.}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
\par 502.15i When a permanent phases out, any local enchantments attached to that permanent phase out at the same time. This alternate way of phasing out is known as phasing out \'93indirectly.\'94 An enchantment that phased out indirectly won\rquote t phase
 in by itself, but instead phases in along with the card it\rquote s attached to.
\par 
\par 502.15j If a local enchantment phased out directly (rather than phasing out along with the permanent it\rquote s attached to), then it \'93remembers\'94 the permanent it was enchanting and retu
rns to play attached to that permanent. If the permanent has left play or is no longer legal to enchant, the enchantment returns to play and then is placed in its owner\rquote s graveyard afterwards. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)
\par 
\par 502.15k If two o
r more permanents phase in at the same time, the active player determines their relative timestamp order at the time they come into play. Local enchantments that phase in indirectly must always have later timestamps than the permanents they enchant, and i
f several enchantments phase in indirectly on the same permanent, their original relative timestamp order must be maintained. (See glossary, \'93Timestamp Order.\'94) This doesn\rquote 
t change the fact that the permanents phase in simultaneously, however. For example, if two Legends with the same name phase in, they both go to their owners\rquote  graveyards.
