\par 503.5. A copy card that comes into play \'93as a copy\'94 of another permanent will come into play with any copied abilities of that permanent. If the copy gains any abilities that modify the comes-into-play event (such as \'93comes into play with\'94 or 
\'93as [this] comes into play\'94 abilities), those abilities will take effect. Also, any comes-into-play triggered abilities of the copy will have a chance to trigger.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example}{\f28 : Skyshroud Behemoth reads, \'93
Fading 2 (This creature comes into play with two fade counters on it. At the beginning of your upkeep, remove a fade counter from it. If you can\rquote t, sacrifice it.) / Skyshroud Behemoth comes into play tapped.\'94
 A Clone that comes into play as a copy of a Skyshroud Behemoth will also come into play tapped with two fade counters on it.
\par }{\b\f28 Example}{\f28 : Striped Bears reads, \'93When Striped Bears comes into play, draw a card.\'94 A Clone comes into play as a copy of Striped Bears. The Clone has the Bears\rquote  comes-into-play triggered ability, so the Clone\rquote 
s controller draws a card.}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.6. When copying a permanent, the \'93choices\'94 of the permanent aren\rquote t copied. Instead, if a card comes into play as a copy of another permanent, the copy\rquote s controller will get to make any \'93as comes into play\'94 choices for it.

\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 A Clone comes int
o play as a copy of Chameleon Spirit. Chameleon Spirit reads, in part, \'93As Chameleon Spirit comes into play, choose a color.\'94 The Clone won\rquote 
t copy the color choice of the Spirit; rather, the controller of the Clone will get to make a new choice.}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.7. Because the \'93choices\'94 of a permanent aren\rquote t copied, sometimes a copy card will gain an ability that refers to a choice that was never made. In that case, the choice is considered to be \'93zero\'94 or \'93undefined.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 Voice of All comes into play and Unstable
 Shapeshifter copies it. Voice of All reads, in part, \'93As Voice of All comes into play, choose a color. / Voice of All has protection from the chosen color.\'94 Unstable Shapeshifter never got a chance to choose a color, because it didn\rquote 
t come into play as a Voice of All card, so the Shapeshifter\rquote s protection ability doesn\rquote t protect it from anything at all.}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.8. If an ability of a copy card causes a player to make a choice as the copy comes into play, the copy will \'93remember\'94 that choice and continue to use it for its abilities if appropriate. If the choice is not appropriate, it is considered to be 
\'93zero\'94 or \'93undefined.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 
A Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of Chameleon Spirit, and the Doppelganger\rquote s controller chooses blue. Later, the Doppelganger copies Quirion Elves. The Elves has the ability, \'93
T: Add one mana of the chosen color to your mana pool.\'94 If the mana ability of the Doppelganger is played, it will produce blue mana.
\par }{\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 A Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of Caller of the Hunt. Caller of the Hunt reads, in part, \'93As Caller of the Hunt comes into play, choose a creature type.\'94 The Doppelganger\rquote 
s controller chooses Goblin. Later, the Doppelganger copies Quirion Elves. If the mana ability of the Doppelganger is played, it will fail to produce any mana. It won\rquote t produce Goblin mana.}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.9. Some copy cards give an ability to the copy as part of the copying process. This ability becomes part of the printed values for the copy, along with any other abilities that were copied. Also, some copy cards specifically state that they don
\rquote t copy certain values; they retain their original values instead.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 
Quirion Elves comes into play and an Unstable Shapeshifter copies it. The printed values of the Shapeshifter now match those of the Elves, except that the Shapeshifter also has the printed ability \'93
Whenever a creature comes into play, Unstable Shapeshifter becomes a copy of that creature and gains this ability.\'94 Then, a Clone comes into play as a copy of the Unstable 
Shapeshifter. The Clone copies the new printed values of the Shapeshifter, including the ability that the Shapeshifter gave itself when it copied the Elves.}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.10. To copy a spell means to put a copy of the spell onto the stack; a copy of a spell isn\rquote t \'93played.\'94
 When copying a spell, all information that is normally copied from a permanent is copied. In addition, all decisions made when the spell was played are copied. These include mode, targets, the value of X, and optional additional costs such as buyb
ack. (See rule 409, \'93Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\'94
) Choices that are normally made on resolution are not copied. A copy of a spell is itself a spell, but it has no spell card associated with it. It works just like a normal spell: It can be count
ered or it can resolve, and it uses the same timing rules as normal spells.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 A player plays Fork, targeting an Emerald Charm. Fork reads, \'93
Put a copy of target instant or sorcery spell onto the stack, except that it copies Fork\rquote s color and you may choose new targets for the copy.\'94 Emerald Charm reads, \'93Choose one \emdash 
 Untap target permanent; or destroy target global enchantment; or target creature loses flying until end of turn.\'94 When the Fork resolves, it puts a copy of the Emerald Charm on the stack.
 The copy has the same mode that was chosen for the original Emerald Charm. It does not necessarily have the same target, but only because Fork allows choosing of new targets.}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-547\li1224\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1224\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 503.10a A copy of a spell in a zone other than the stack ceases to exist. (This
 is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
503.11. If an effect refers to a permanent by name, the effect still tracks that permanent even if it changes names or becomes a copy of something else.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 An Unstable Shapeshifter copies a Crazed Armodon. Crazed Armodon reads, 
\'93G: Crazed Armodon gets +3/+0 and gains trample until end of turn. Destroy Crazed Armodon at end of turn. Play this ability only once each turn.\'94 If this activated ability of the Shapeshifter is played, the Shapeshifter will be destroye
d at end of turn, even if it\rquote s no longer a copy of Crazed Armodon at that time.}{\b\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 504. Face-Down Spells and Permanents
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
504.1. One old card (Illusionary Mask) and the morph ability (see rule 502.26) allow spells and permanents to be face down.
\par 
\par 504.2. Face-
down cards on the stack, face-down cards and tokens in play, and face-down cards in the phased-out zone have no characteristics other than those listed by the card or rules that allow the card or token to be face down. Any listed characteristics are that 
card or token\rquote s initial characteristics. Permanents that are put into play face down are turned face down before they come into play, so the permanent\rquote s comes-into-play abilities won\rquote 
t trigger (if triggered) or have any effect (if static). Spells that are played face down are turned face down before they are put onto the stack, so effects that care about the characteristics of a spell will see only the face-down spell\rquote 
s characteristics.
\par 
\par 504.3. You may look at a face-down spell you control on the stack or a face-down permanent you control at any time. You can\rquote 
t look at face-down cards in any other zone or face-down spells or permanents controlled by another player. The card or rules that allow a permanent to be face down may also allow the permanent\rquote s controller to turn it face up. Spells normally can
\rquote t be turned face up.
\par 
\par 504.4. If you control multiple face-down spells on the stack or face-down permanents in play, you must ensure at all times that your face-down spells and permanents can be easily differentia
ted from each other. This includes, but is not limited to, knowing the order spells were played, the order that face-down permanents came into play, which creature attacked last turn, and any other differences between face-down spells or permanents. Commo
n methods for distinguishing between face-down cards include using counters or dice to mark the different permanents, or clearly placing those permanents in order on the table.
\par 
\par 504.5. As a face-down permanent is turned face up, its initial characteristics 
revert to its normal initial characteristics. Any effects that have been applied to the face-down permanent still apply to the face-up permanent. Any abilities relating to the permanent coming into play don\rquote t trigger and don\rquote 
t have any effect, because the permanent has already come into play.
\par 
\par 504.6. If a face-down permanent moves from the in-play zone to any zone other than the phased-out zone, its owner must reveal it to all players as he or she moves it. If a face-down spell moves from the stack to any z
one other than the in-play zone, its owner must reveal it to all players as he or she moves it. At the end of each game, all face-down spells and permanents must be revealed to all players.
\par }\pard\plain \s18\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 505. Split Cards
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {505.1. }{\i Split cards}{ have two card faces on a sin
gle card. The back of a split card is the normal }{\b Magic: The Gathering}{ card back.
\par 
\par 505.2. In every zone except the stack, split cards have two sets of characteristics. As long as a split card is on the stack, only the characteristics of the half being played exist. The other half\rquote s characteristics are treated as though they didn
\rquote t exist.
\par 
\par 505.3. Because every split card consists of two halves with different colored mana symbols in their mana costs, each split card is a multicolored card except while it\rquote s on the stack. While it\rquote s on the stack, it\rquote 
s only the color of the half being played.
\par 
\par 505.4. Although split cards have two playable halves, each split card is only one card. For example, a player who has drawn or discarded a split card has drawn or discarded one card, not two.
\par 
\par 505.5. Effects that ask for a particular characteristic of a split card while it\rquote s in a zone other than the stack get an answer that consists of a combination of the split card\rquote s two halves.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  Infernal Genesis has an ability that reads, \'93
At the beginning of each player\rquote s upkeep, that player puts the top card of his or her library into his or her graveyard. He or she then puts X 1/1 black Minion creature tokens into play, where X is that card\rquote s converted mana cost.\'94
 If the top card of your library is Assault/Battery when this ability resolves, you get five 1/1 creature tokens because Assault\rquote s converted mana cost is 1 and Battery\rquote s is 4, for a total of 5.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 505.6. Effects that ask if a split card\rquote s characteristic matches a given value get only one answer. This answer is \'93yes\'94 if either side of the split card matches the given value.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example:}{\f28  Void reads, \'93
Choose a number. Destroy all artifacts and creatures with converted mana cost equal to that number. Then target player reveals his or her hand and discards from it all nonland cards with converted mana cost equal to the number.\'94
 If a player plays Void and chooses 1 or 4, his or her opponent would discard Assault/Battery. If the player chooses 5, Assault/Battery would be unaffected, because neither half has a converted mana cost of 5.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \fi-432\li749\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin749\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 505.7. If an effect instructs a player to name a card and the player wants to name a split card, the player must name both halves of the split card.
\par }\pard\plain \qc \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 \page }{\b\f28 Glossary
\par }{\f28\fs22\cf13 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f28\fs22 Ability
\par \'93Ability\'94 and \'93effect\'94 are often confused with one another. An instruction in a card\rquote s or permanent\rquote s text is an ability. The result of following such an instruction, or of following a spell\rquote s instruction, is an effect.

\par      A card or permanent may have one or more abilities or no abilities at all. For more information, see section 4, \'93Spells, Abilities, and Effects.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28      When an effect states that a card or permanent \'93gains\'94 or \'93
has\'94 an ability, it\rquote s granting that card or permanent an ability. If an effect defines a characteristic of a card or permanent (\'93[card or permanent] is [characteristic]\'94), it\rquote 
s not granting an ability. For example, an enchant creature might read, \'93Enchanted creature is red.\'94 The enchantment isn\rquote t granting an ability of any kind; it\rquote s simply changing the enchanted creature\rquote s color to red.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Activated Ability
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 An activated ability is written as \'93activation cost: effect.\'94
 By paying the activation cost, a player may play such }{\f28 an }{\f28 abilit}{\f28 y}{\f28  whenever he or she has priority. See rule 403, \'93Activated Abilities.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Activation Cost
\par The activation cost of an activated ability is everything before the colon in \'93activation cost: effect.\'94 It must be paid to play the ability. For example, the activation cost of an ability that reads \'932, T: Gain 1 life\'94
 is two mana of any color plus tapping the permanent. See rule 403, \'93Activated Abilities.\'94
\par 
\par Active Player
\par The active player is the player whose turn it is. The active player gets priority at the start of each phase or step (except for the untap and cleanup steps), after any spell or ability (except a mana ability) resolves, and after combat damage resolves.

\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
     Whenever both players are instructed to make choices at the same time, the active player makes all his or her choices first, then the nonactive player.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Additional Cost
\par Some spells have additional costs listed in their text. These are paid at the same time the player pays the spell\rquote s mana cost. See rule 409, \'93Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\'94
\par 
\par Alternative Cost
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 The rules text of some spells reads, \'93
You may [action] rather than pay [this card\rquote s] mana cost.\'94 These are alternative costs. Other spells and abilities that refer to a spell\rquote s mana cost don\rquote 
t consider the alternative cost. If an effect requires paying additional costs to play a spell, it still applies to the alternative cost.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par }\pard\plain \s29\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af4\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 \hich\af28\dbch\af4\loch\f28 Amplify
\par \hich\af28\dbch\af4\loch\f28 \hich\f28 Amplify is a static ability. \'93\loch\f28 \hich\f28 Amplify [X]\'94\loch\f28 \hich\f28  means \'93\loch\f28 
As this card comes into play, reveal any number of cards from your hand that share a creature type with this card. This card comes into play with X +1/+1 counters on it for each card revealed this\hich\af28\dbch\af4\loch\f28  way. You can\hich\f28 
\rquote \loch\f28 \hich\f28 t reveal this card or any other cards that are coming into play at the same time as this card.\'94\loch\f28 \hich\f28  See rule 502.27, \'93\loch\f28 \hich\f28 Amplify.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 Ante (Obsolete)
\par Earlier versions of the }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  rules included an ante rule as a way of playing \'93for keeps.\'94 Playing }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22 
 for ante is now considered an optional variation on the game, and it is allowed only where it\rquote 
s not forbidden by law or by other rules. Playing for ante is strictly forbidden under DCI tournament rules. When using the ante rule, each player puts one ra
ndom card from his or her deck into his or her ante zone at the beginning of the game. At the end of the game, the winner becomes the owner of the cards in each player\rquote s ante zone. See rule 217.9, \'93Ante.\'94
\par 
\par Artifact
\par Artifact is both a card type and a permanent type. The active player can play artifact spells only during his or her main phase when the stack is empty.
\par 
\par Artifact Creature
\par This permanent is a combination of artifact and creature, and it\rquote s subject to the rules for both. (See rule 214, \'93Permanent Type.\'94) Some artifact creatures don\rquote t have a creature type. Those that do will say \'93Artifact Creature 
\emdash  [creature type]\'94; for example, \'93Artifact Creature \emdash  Golem.\'94 \'93Artifact\'94 isn\rquote t a creature type.
\par 
\par \'93As though\'94
\par Text that states a player or card may do something \'93as though\'94
 some condition were true applies only to the stated action. For purposes of that action, treat the game exactly as if the stated condition is true. For all other purposes, treat the game normally.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example}{\f28 : \'93Giant Spider may block as though it had flying.\'94
 You may treat the Spider as a creature with flying, but only for the purpose of declaring blockers. This allows Giant Spider to block a creature with flying (and creatures that \'93can\rquote t be blocked except by creatures with flying\'94), assuming 
no other blocking restrictions apply. For example, Giant Spider can\rquote t normally block a creature with both flying and shadow.
\par }{\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 \'93You may play that card as though it were in your hand.\'94 The card may be played by the usual rules. If it\rquote s a spell, it\rquote s placed on the stack as the first step of playing it (see rule 409, \'93
Playing Spells and Activated Abilities\'94); if it\rquote s a land, it\rquote s put directly into play. Because the card isn\rquote t actually in your hand, it can\rquote t be discarded, removed from the game to pay a c
ost, cycled, or counted toward the number of cards in your hand.
\par }{\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 \'93Walls may attack as though they weren\rquote t Walls.\'94 As long as this effect is active, Walls are treated exactly like creatures that don\rquote t have the Wall creature type. They\rquote re still subj
ect to all other rules and effects that determine whether an attack is legal.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22      If two cards state that a player or card may do the same thing \'93as though\'94
 different conditions were true, both conditions could apply. If one \'93as though\'94 effect satisfies the requirements for another \'93as though\'94 effect, then both effects will apply.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 \i\f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f28 Example: }{\f28 Two effects state, \'93
You may play cards in your graveyard as though they were in your hand,\'94 and \'93You may play cards from other players\rquote  graveyards as though they were in your graveyard.\'94
 Both effects apply. You may play cards in your graveyard and cards in your opponents\rquote  graveyards. (The cards may be played by the usual rules.)
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Attack
\par A creature attacks when it is declared as an attacker during the combat phase. (See rule 308, \'93Declare Attackers Step.\'94) Playing a spell or ability (even during the combat phase) is never considered to be an attack.
\par 
\par Attack Alone
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 A creature is attacking alone when it\rquote 
s the sole creature declared as an attacker in a given combat phase.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Attacked
\par Some triggered abilities trigger when a player is \'93attacked.\'94 At least one creature must actually be attacking that player for such abilities to trigger. Also, \'93attacked\'94 means \'93attacked by one or more creatures,\'94
 so such abilities can trigger only once each combat phase.
\par 
\par Attacking Creature
\par A creature becomes an attacking creature when (a) it\rquote s declared as part of a legal attack during the combat phase and (b) all attack costs have been paid. It remains an attacking creature until it\rquote s removed from co
mbat, it stops being a creature, its controller changes, or the combat phase ends. Attacking creatures don\rquote t exist outside of the combat phase. See rule 308, \'93Declare Attackers Step.\'94
\par 
\par Attacks and Isn\rquote t Blocked
\par An ability that triggers when a creature \'93attacks and isn\rquote t blocked\'94 triggers when the creature becomes an unblocked attacking creature. See rule 309.3.
\par 
\par Banding, \'93Bands with Other\'94
\par Banding is a static ability that affects the combat phase. \'93Bands with other\'94 is a specialized version of the ability. See rule 502.10, \'93Banding,\'94 and rule 502.11, \'93Bands with Other.\'94
\par 
\par Basic Land
\par There are five basic land types: plains, island, swamp, mountain, and forest. Any land whose name is one of these five types is a basic land. Every basic land has an intrinsic mana ability. (See rule 214.9, \'93Lands.\'94
) Snow-covered lands are still basic lands. For example, Snow-Covered Plains is considered a plains.
\par 
\par Becomes
\par Some trigger events use the word \'93becomes\'94 (for example, \'93becomes tappe}{\f28\fs22\expnd4\expndtw20 d}{\f28\fs22 \'94 or \'93becomes blocked\'94). These trigger only at the time the named event happens\emdash they don\rquote 
t trigger if that state already exists or retrigger if it persists. For example, \'93becomes tapped\'94 triggers only once and only when a permanent\rquote s status changes from untapped to tapped.
\par 
\par Beginning Phase
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 The
 beginning phase is the first phase of the turn. It has three steps: untap, upkeep, and draw. See rule 301, \'93Beginning Phase.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Block
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 A creature blocks when it\rquote 
s declared as a blocker during the combat phase. See rule 309, \'93Declare Blockers Step.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Block Alone
\par A creature is blocking alone when it\rquote s the sole creature declared as a blocker in a given combat phase.
\par 
\par Blocked Creature
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
An attacking creature becomes a blocked creature when another creature blocks it or an effect causes it to become blocked during the combat phase. It remains a blocked creature until it\rquote 
s removed from combat, it stops being a creature, its controller changes, or the combat phase ends. A blocked creature doesn\rquote t become unblocked if the blocking creature is later removed from combat. Blocked creatures don\rquote 
t exist outside of the combat phase. See rule 309, \'93Declare Blockers Step.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Blocking Creature
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 A creature becomes a blocking creature when (a) it\rquote 
s declared as part of a legal block during the combat phase and (b) all block costs have been paid. It remains a blocking creature until it\rquote 
s removed from combat, it stops being a creature, its controller changes, or the combat phase ends. Blocking creatures don\rquote t exist outside of the combat phase. See rule 309, \'93Declare Blockers Step.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Bury (Obsolete)
\par Some older cards were printed with the term \'93bury,\'94 which meant to put a permanent into its owner\rquote s graveyard. In general, cards that were printed with the term \'93bury\'94 now read, \'93Destroy [a permanent]. It can\rquote t be regenerated.
\'94
\par 
\par Buyback
\par Buyback
 is a replacement effect modifying rule 413.2h. When playing an instant or sorcery spell with buyback, the controller of the spell may pay an additional cost specified on the card. If he or she does, when the spell resolves, the card is put into his or he
r hand instead of into his or her graveyard. If the card goes to some zone other than its owner\rquote s graveyard as it resolves, buyback\rquote s effect \'93loses track\'94 of it, and the card isn\rquote t returned to its owner\rquote s hand.
\par 
\par Cantrip (Informal)
\par This is a nickname for any spell that has \'93Draw a car}{\f28\fs22\expnd4\expndtw20 d}{\f28\fs22 \'94 as part of its effect.
\par 
\par Card
\par This is specifically a }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  card, and is always considered a card regardless of which zone it\rquote s in. Tokens aren\rquote t cards. See section 2, \'93Cards.\'94
\par 
\par Cast (Obsolete)
\par Some older cards were used the term \'93cast\'94 to describe the playing of a spell. In general, cards that were printed with the term \'93cast\'94 now use the term \'93play.\'94
\par 
\par Caster (Obsolete)
\par Some older cards used the term \'93caster\'94 to describe the player who played a spell. In general, cards that were printed with the term \'93caster\'94 now refer to the spell\rquote s \'93controller.\'94
\par 
\par Casting Cost (Obsolete)
\par Some older cards used the term \'93casting cost\'94 to describe the mana cost of a spell. In general, cards that were printed with the term \'93casting cost\'94 now use the term \'93mana cost.\'94 Cards that used the term \'93total casting cost\'94
 now use the term \'93converted mana cost.\'94
\par 
\par Characteristics
\par A card, spell, or permanent\rquote s characteristics are name, mana cost, color, type and subtype, expansion symbol, rules text, power, and toughness. A card, spell, or permanent\rquote 
s characteristics at any given time start with the initial values, then are adjusted by any counters (on a permanen}{\f28\fs22\expnd4\expndtw20 t}{\f28\fs22 ), then by continuous effects. Characteristics don\rquote 
t include any other information, such as whether a permanent is tapped, a spell or permanent\rquote s controller, a spell\rquote s target, what a local enchantment enchants, and so on.
\par 
\par Cleanup
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
Cleanup is the second and final step of the end phase. Spells and abilities may be played during this step only if the conditions for any state-based effects exist or if any abilities have triggered. In that case, the step repeats. See rule 314, \'93
Cleanup Step.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Color
\par The only colors in the }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic }{\f28\fs22 game are white, blue, black, red, and green. A permanent can be one or more of those colors or it can be colorless. \'93Colorless\'94 isn\rquote t a color; neither are \'93artifact,\'94 \'93land,\'94 
\'93brown,\'94 and so on.
\par      A card\rquote s initial color is determined by the color(s) of the mana symbols in its mana cost.
\par      Spells and abilities may change a permanent\rquote s color temporarily or permanently. If an effect gives a permanent a new color, the new color replaces all previous colors the permanent had.
\par 
\par Colorless
\par A card with no color is colorless. Lands are colorless because they have no mana cost. Artifacts are col
orless because they have no colored mana in their mana costs. Face-down creatures are colorless due to the effects that turn them face down. A colorless spell or permanent can be given a color by an effect.
\par 
\par Colorless mana
\par The numeral mana symbols, X, and Y can represent colorless mana as well as a generic mana cost.
\par 
\par Combat Damage
\par Combat damage is dealt during the combat damage step of the combat phase by attacking creatures and blocking creatures. It doesn\rquote t include damage dealt by spells and abilities during the combat phase. See rule 310, \'93Combat Damage Step.\'94

\par 
\par Combat Phase
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
Combat is the third phase of the turn. The combat phase has five steps: beginning of combat, declare attackers, declare blockers, combat damage, and end of combat. See rules 306\endash 311.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Comes into Play
\par A permanent comes into play when the card or token representing it is moved into the in-play zone. A permanent whose type or controller changes doesn\rquote t \'93come into play.\'94
\par      Permanents come into play untapped and under the control of whoever put them into play.
\par      Instructions that alter permanents coming into play do so as they come into play. For example, if an instruction causes something to come into play tapped, it isn\rquote t put into play untapped and then tapped. The controller-to-be o
f that permanent makes any choices required by the instruction.
\par      When a permanent comes into play, first apply any \'93as [this card] comes into play\'94 text, then apply any \'93[this card] comes into play with\'94 text, then apply continuous effects, then check 
to determine if the current form of the permanent generates any triggered abilities.
\par 
\par Continuous Ability (Obsolete)
\par In earlier versions of the rules, static abilities were known as \'93continuous abilities.\'94
\par 
\par Continuous Effect
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 Continuous effects are usually a
ctive as long as the permanent with the associated static ability remains in play or the card with the associated static ability remains in the appropriate zone. A spell or ability can also create a continuous effect that doesn\rquote 
t depend on a permanent; these last for the specified time. See rule 418, \'93Continuous Effects.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Continuous Artifact (Obsolete)
\par Earlier versions of the rules provided support for a \'93continuous artifact\'94 card type. All continuous artifact cards are now simply artifact cards. Artifacts printed with the continuous artifact card type generally have no activated abilities.
\par 
\par Control, Controller
\par Every permanent, spell, and ability has a controller.
\par      When a permanent comes into play, its controller is whoever put it into play unless the spell or ability that generated the permanent states otherwise. Other effects can later change a permanent\rquote s controller.
\par      Cards in zones other than in play or the stack have no controller. A spell or activated ability on the stack is controlled by whoever played it. A triggered ability is controlled by the player who controlled its source at the time it triggered.

\par 
\par Converted Mana Cost
\par The converted mana cost of a card is the total amount of mana in its mana cost, regardless of color. For example, Air Elemental has a mana cost of 3UU and a converted mana cost of 5. See rule 203, \'93Mana Cost.\'94
\par 
\par Copy Card
\par A \'93copy card\'94 is a card that creates or becomes a \'93copy\'94 of a spell, permanent, or card. See rule 503, \'93Copying Spells and Abilities.\'94
\par 
\par Cost
\par Playing spells and activated abilities requires paying a cost. Most costs are paid in mana, but they may also include paying life, tapping or sacrificing permanents, discarding cards, and so on.
\par      It\rquote s illegal to pay a cost without having the necessary resources to pay it fully. For example, a player with only 1 life can\rquote t pay a cost of 2 life, and a permanent that\rquote s already tapped can\rquote 
t be tapped to pay a cost. See rule 203, \'93Mana Cost,\'94 and rule 403, \'93Activated Abilities.\'94
\par 
\par Counter
\par Counter has two meanings in the }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  game.
\par      1. To counter a spell or ability is to cancel it, removing it from the stack zone. It doesn\rquote t resolve and none of its effects occur. A countered spell is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard.
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28      }{\f28 2. A counter is a marker placed on a permanent, eit
her modifying its characteristics or interacting with an ability. A +X/+Y counter on a permanent, where X and Y are numbers, adds X to that permanent\rquote s power and Y to that permanent\rquote 
s toughness. These bonuses are added after permanent-type changing effects
 and before other power and toughness changing effects. Counters with the same name or description are interchangeable. Counters may also be given to players. For information about poison counters, see rule 102.8.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Counts As (Obsolete)
\par Some older cards were printed with text stating that the card \'93counts as\'94 something. As far as the game rules and other cards are concerned the card is that thing. (Newer }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  cards use \'93is\'94 instead.) This isn
\rquote t an ability; it applies even when the card\rquote s not in play. For example, a card that \'93counts as a forest\'94
 can be retrieved with a spell that searches the library for a forest card, and once in play it may be tapped for green mana and allows forestwalk.
\par 
\par Creature
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 Creature is both a card type and permanent type. The active
 player can play creature spells only during his or her main phase when the stack is empty. See rule 214.7, \'93Creatures.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Cumulative Upkeep
\par Cumulative upkeep is a triggered ability. \'93Cumulative upkeep [cos}{\f28\fs22\expnd4\expndtw20 t}{\f28\fs22 ]\'94 means \'93At the beginning of your upkeep, put an 
age counter on this permanent, then sacrifice this permanent unless you pay [cost] for each age counter on it.\'94
 Note that if a permanent has more than one instance of cumulative upkeep, each creates a separate triggered ability at the beginning of upkeep that counts all the age counters on the permanent from }{\i\f28\fs22 both}{\f28\fs22 
 abilities. See rule 502.13, \'93Cumulative Upkeep.\'94
\par 
\par Cycling
\par Cycling is an activated ability. \'93Cycling [cos}{\f28\fs22\expnd4\expndtw20 t}{\f28\fs22 ]\'94 means \'93[Cost], Discard this car}{\f28\fs22\expnd2\expndtw10 d from your hand}{\f28\fs22 : Draw a card.\'94 See rule 502.18, \'93Cycling.\'94
\par 
\par Damage
\par Many spells and abilities deal damage to creatures and/or players. Creatures may also deal combat damage during the combat phase.
\par      Damage dealt to a player is subtracted from his or her life total.
\par      Damage dealt to a creature stays on the permanent, even if it stops being a creature. A creature with damage greater than or equal to its toughness (and greater than 0) has been dealt lethal damage and is destroyed. (See rule 420, \'93
State-Based Effects.\'94) Damage doesn\rquote t alter a creature\rquote s toughness. A noncreature permanent isn\rquote 
t affected by damage (but if it becomes a creature again before the damage is removed, the creature may be destroyed). During the cleanup step, all damage is removed from permanents.
\par      Costs and effects that read \'93lose life\'94 or \'93pay life\'94 don\rquote t deal damage, and that loss of life can\rquote t be prevented or otherwise altered by damage-prevention effects.
\par 
\par Damage-Prevention Ability
\par A damage-prevention ability is a static or activated ability that generates a damage-prevention effect. See rule 419.7, \'93Prevention Effects.\'94
\par 
\par Deck
\par A player\rquote s deck is the collection of cards that player starts the game with. When the game begins, each player\rquote s deck becomes his or her library.
\par 
\par Defending Player
\par During the combat phase, the active player\rquote 
s opponent is the defending player. (In a multiplayer game, there may be one defending player at a time or there may be more than one, depending on which variant is being played.) Creatures can attack only the defending player; they can\rquote 
t attack other players or creatures. During phases other than combat, there is no defending player.
\par 
\par Delayed Triggered Ability
\par A delayed triggered ability is created by effects generated when some spells or abilities resolve. See rule 406.2, \'93Delayed Triggered Abilities.\'94
\par 
\par Destroy
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 To destroy a permanent is to move it from the in-play zone to its owner
\rquote s graveyard. Regeneration or other destruction-replacement effects can replace this action. See rule 419, \'93Replacement and Prevention Effects.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Discard
\par A player discards a card
 by putting a card from his or her hand into his or her graveyard. By default, spells and abilities that cause a player to discard a card allow the affected player to choose which card to discard. Some spells and abilities, however, require a random disca
rd or allow another player to choose which card is discarded.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s29\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af4\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 \hich\af28\dbch\af4\loch\f28 Double strike
\par \hich\af28\dbch\af4\loch\f28 Double strike is a static ability that modifies the rules for the combat damage step. Creatures with double strike deal combat damage in both the first strike combat damage step an\hich\af28\dbch\af4\loch\f28 \hich\f28 
d the normal combat damage step. See rule 502.28, \'93\loch\f28 \hich\f28 Double Strike.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 Draw
\par Draw has two meanings in the }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  game.
\par      1. A player draws a card by putting the top card of his or her library into his or her hand. A spell or ability may move cards from a player\rquote s library to that player\rquote s hand without the player \'93drawing\'94
 them; this makes a difference for abilities that trigger on drawing cards or that replace card draws.
\par      2. A game ends in a draw if both players lose or win simultaneously.
\par 
\par Draw Step
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 The 
draw step is the third step of the beginning phase, with a triggered ability that requires the active player to draw a card at the beginning of the step. A player may play spells and abilities during this step }{\f28 
whenever he or she has priority. See rule 304, \'93Draw Step.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Dual Land (Informal)
\par Ten \'93dual land\'94 cards were printed in early }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  editions; each of these has two basic land types in addition to its inherent land type. For example, Taiga has the land types Taiga, forest, and mountain. Dual land cards
 have the default abilities of both basic land types and are treated as both by all spells and abilities that specifically refer to those types. However, they are not basic lands. A dual land card doesn\rquote t count as two lands while in play\emdash it
\rquote s just one land with multiple land types. Changing one of the land type words on a dual land also changes which mana ability it has. Thus, if you play a spell or ability that edits Taiga to read, \'93
Taiga is a plains and a forest in addition to its land type,\'94 it could then be tapped for white or green mana.
\par 
\par Duel (Obsolete)
\par In earlier versions of the rules, a game of }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  was known as a \'93duel.\'94 }{\i\f28\fs22 See also}{\f28\fs22  Match.
\par 
\par During (Obsolete)
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 Earlier versions of the rules provided support for \'93phase abilities,
\'94 which were written \'93During [phase], [action].\'94 In general, cards that were printed with phase abilities now have abilities that trigger at the beginning of a step or phase. \'93During\'94
 still appears in current card text, but only in its normal English sense and not as game terminology.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Echo
\par Echo is a triggered ability. \'93Echo\'94 means \'93At the beginning of your upkeep, if this permanent came under your control since the beginning of your last upkeep, sacrifice it unless you pay its mana cost.\'94 See rule 502.19, \'93Echo.\'94
\par 
\par Effect
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 \'93Ability\'94 and \'93effect\'94
 are often confused with one another. An instruction in a permanent\rquote s text is an ability. The result of carrying out such an instruction, or that of a spell, is an effect. See rule 416, \'93Effects.\'94
