\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 When a spell or ability on top of t
he stack resolves, its controller carries out the instructions printed on the card, in the order written. When combat damage resolves, it\rquote s dealt as previously assigned to the fullest extent possible. See rule 413, \'93
Resolving Spells and Abilities.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Respond, Response (Informal)
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
A player can choose to play an instant spell or activated ability when something else is already on the stack, rather than waiting for the earlier spell or ability to resolve first. The spell or ability is said to be played \'93in response to\'94
 the earlier spell or ability.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Reveal
\par To reveal a card is to show that card to all players. This is a one-shot effec}{\f28\fs22\expnd2\expndtw10 t}{\f28\fs22 ; after all players have seen the card, it\rquote s returned to its former state.
\par 
\par Sacrifice
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 To sacrifice a permanent, its controller move
s it from the in-play zone directly to its owner\rquote s graveyard. If an effect instructs a player to sacrifice a permanent that he or she doesn\rquote t control, nothing happens. Sacrificing a permanent doesn\rquote 
t destroy it, so regeneration or other effects that replace destruction can\rquote t affect it.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Search
\par If you\rquote re required to search a zone not revealed to all players for cards matching some criteria, you aren\rquote t required to find those cards even if they\rquote re present. Even if you don\rquote t find any cards, you are still consid
ered to have searched the zone. If you\rquote re simply searching for \'93any card,\'94 however, you must find a card (if possible). If you\rquote 
re required to search for a specific number of cards, you must choose that many cards (or as many as possible.) For example, if an effect causes you to search a player\rquote 
s library for all duplicates of a particular card and remove them from the game, you may choose to leave some of them alone, but if an effect causes you to search your library for three cards and it contains at least three, you can\rquote 
t choose less than three.
\par 
\par Separating Cards into Piles
\par If a player is asked to separate a group of cards into two or more piles, the cards do not leave the zone they\rquote re currently in. If cards in a graveyard are split into piles, the order of the graveyard must be maintained as much as possible.
\par 
\par Set Aside
\par To set aside a card is to remove it from the game; however, the effect will specify some condition that allows the set-aside card to return to the game. }{\i\f28\fs22 See also}{\f28\fs22  Removed from the Game.
\par 
\par Shadow
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 Shadow is an evasion ability. Attacking creatures with shadow can\rquote 
t be blocked by creatures without shadow, and attacking creatures without shadow can\rquote t be blocked by creatures with shadow. See rule 502.8, \'93Shadow.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Skip
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 To skip a step, phase, or turn is to proceed past it as though it didn
\rquote t exist. Skipping is a replacement effect. \'93Skip [something]\'94 is the same as \'93Instead of doing [something], do nothing.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22      Once a step, phase, or turn has started, it can no longer be skipped\emdash 
any skip effects will wait until the next occurrence.
\par      Anything scheduled for a skipped step, phase, or turn won\rquote t happen. Anything scheduled for the \'93next\'94 occurrence of something waits for the first occurrence that isn\rquote t skipped. If two effects each cause a player to ski
p his or her next occurrence, that player must skip the next two; one effect will be satisfied in skipping the first occurrence, while the other will remain until another occurrence can be skipped.
\par 
\par Snow-Covered
\par Snow-covered is an ability that doesn\rquote t do anything in its own right; it\rquote s simply a keyword that other cards look for. When a card refers to a \'93snow-covered land,\'94 it means a land with the snow-covered ability. When a card refers to a 
\'93snow-covered forest,\'94 it means a forest with the snow-covered ability, and so on. See rule 502.14, \'93Snow-Covered.\'94
\par 
\par Snow-Covered Landwalk
\par Snow-covered landwalk is a special form of landwalk. A creature with snow-covered landwalk is unblockable as long as the defending player controls at least one land of the specified type that has the snow-covered ability. See rule 502.6, \'93Landwalk.\'94

\par 
\par Sorcery
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
Sorcery is a card type. The active player can play sorcery spells only during his or her main phase when the stack is empty. A sorcery spell is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard as part of its resolution. See rule 408.1d.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Source
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
The source of an ability or of damage is the card or token that generated it. If an effect requires a player to choose a source, he or she may choose either a permanent or a spell on the stack (including one 
that creates a permanent) or any card or permanent referred to by a spell or pseudospell on the stack. The effect will apply in the way specified to the damage dealt by that spell or by that permanent (in combat or by one of its abilities). A source doesn
\rquote t need to be capable of dealing damage to be a legal choice.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Spell
\par A nonland card becomes a spell when it\rquote s played and remains a spell until it\rquote s countered or it resolves. A copy of a spell is also a spell, even if it has no card associated with it. Nonland cards can also be referred to as \'93spell cards.
\'94 See rule 401, \'93Spells.\'94
\par 
\par Split Cards
\par Split cards have two card faces on a single card. The back of a split card is the normal, full-size }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  card back. Split cards have two sets of characteristics: two n
ames, two mana costs, and so on. They always have both sets, except when they\rquote re on the stack. When you play a split card, you announce which side of the card you\rquote re playing. While it\rquote 
s on the stack, the other side of the card is ignored completely.
\par      Split cards have two mana costs with different colors of mana in them. That means they are multicolored cards, except while they\rquote re on the stack. If an effect tells you to name a card, you must name all of a split card\rquote s names.
\par      Effects that ask for a split card\rquote s characteristic get both answers. Effects that ask if a split card\rquote s characteristic matches a given value get only one answer. This answer is \'93yes\'94
 if either side of the split card matches the given value. See rule 505, \'93Split Cards.\'94
\par 
\par Stack
\par A spell or ability goes on top of the stack when it\rquote 
s played or triggered. Combat-damage assignments also go on top of the stack as though they were a single pseudospell. Whenever both players pass in succession, the spell, ability, or combat damage on top of
 the stack resolves and the active player receives priority again. See rule 217.6, \'93Stack,\'94 and rule 408.1, \'93Timing, Priority, and the Stack.\'94
\par 
\par State-Based Effects
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 State-based effects continually \'93watch\'94
 the game for a particular state. Whenever a player would receive priority, state-based effects are checked and applied. See rule 420, \'93State-Based Effects.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par State Triggers
\par State triggers are triggered abilities that watch for a game state rather than an event and trigger as soon as the game state matches the condition. Once a state trigger has triggered, it won\rquote 
t trigger again until the pseudospell it created has resolved or been countered. See rule 410.11.
\par 
\par Static Ability
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
Static abilities do something all the time rather than being played at specific times
. Static abilities create continuous effects, which are active as long as the permanent with the ability remains in play and has the ability, or as long as the card with the ability remains in the appropriate zone. A spell or ability can also create a con
tinuous effect that doesn\rquote t depend on a permanent; these may last a specified length of time or for the rest of the game. See rule 412, \'93Handling Static Abilities.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Step
\par Some }{\i\f28\fs22 phases}{\f28\fs22  of the turn are further subdivided into steps. See section 3, \'93Turn Structure.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s29\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af4\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 \hich\af28\dbch\af4\loch\f28 Storm
\par \hich\af28\dbch\af4\loch\f28 \hich\f28 Storm is a triggered ability that functions while the card is on the stack. \'93\loch\f28 \hich\f28 Storm\'94\loch\f28 \hich\f28  means \'93\loch\f28 
When you play this spell, put a copy of it onto the stack for each other spell that was played before it this turn. If the spell has any targets, you ma\hich\af28\dbch\af4\loch\f28 \hich\f28 y choose new targets for any number of the copies.\'94\loch\f28 
\hich\f28  See rule 502.30, \'93\loch\f28 \hich\f28 Storm.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 Successfully Cast (Obsolete)
\par Earlier versions of the rules provided support for \'93successfully cast\'94 as a step in the announcement and resolution of a spell or ability. In general, any ability that\rquote s written as triggering when a spell is \'93successfully cast\'94
 should be read as triggering when the spell is played.
\par 
\par Summon (Obsolete)
\par Older creature cards were printed with the type \'93Summon [creature subtype].\'94 All \'93Summon [creature subtype]\'94 cards should be read as \'93Creature \emdash  [creature subtype].\'94
\par 
\par Summoning Sickness (Obsolete)
\par In earlier versions of the rules, the term \'93summoning sickness\'94 was used to describe a creature\rquote s inability to attack or to use activated abilities that include the tap symbol when it has come under a player\rquote 
s control since the beginning of that player\rquote s most recent turn. }{\i\f28\fs22 See also}{\f28\fs22  Haste.
\par 
\par Swampcycling}{\i\f28\fs22 See}{\f28\fs22  Landcycling.Swampwalk
\par }{\i\f28\fs22 See}{\f28\fs22  Landwalk.
\par 
\par Tap
\par To tap a permanent is to turn it sideways. The tap symbol (T in these rules) in an activation cost means \'93Tap this permanent\'94\emdash a permanent that\rquote s already tapped can\rquote t be tapped again to pay the cost. Creatures that haven\rquote 
t been under a player\rquote s control continuously since the beginning of his or her most recent turn can\rquote t use any ability with the tap symbol in the cost.
\par 
\par Target
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 Whenever the word \'93target\'94
 appears in the rules text of a spell or ability, the controller of the spell or ability chooses something that matches whatever follows that word. This may be as simple as \'93target lan}{\f28\expnd2\expndtw10 d}{\f28 \'94 }{\f28 or as complex as \'93
target tapped creature an opponent controls.\'94 The choice of a spell or ability\rquote s targets is made when the spell or ability is played.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22      A spell or pseudospell on the stack can\rquote t target itself.
\par 
\par Text Box
\par The text box is printed below the illustration on a }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  card and contains rules, reminder text, and flavor text.
\par 
\par }{\f28\fs22\cf1 Threshold
\par Threshold is a static ability. A card with threshold has the text after \'93Threshold \emdash \'94 if its controller has seven or more cards in his or her graveyard. Otherwise, the text after \'93Threshold \emdash \'94
 is treated as though it did not appear on the card. An instant or sorcery card with threshold has the threshold text only if the card is on the stack. An artifact, creature, enchantment, or land card with thresho
ld, or any permanent with threshold, has the threshold text only if the card or permanent is in play.}{\f28\fs22  See rule 502.23, \'93Threshold.\'94
\par 
\par Tie
\par If an effect could result in a tie, the text of the spell or ability that created the effect will specify what to do in the event of a tie. The }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  game has no default for ties.
\par 
\par Timestamp Order
\par A card or permanent\rquote s timestamp is the time it entered the zone it\rquote s currently in, with two exceptions: (1) If two or more cards or permanents enter a zone simultaneously, the ac
tive player determines their timestamp order at the time they enter that zone, but a local enchantment must be timestamped after what it enchants. (2) Whenever a local enchantment becomes attached to a permanent, the enchantment receives a new timestamp.

\par  
    Continuous effects generated by static abilities have the same timestamp as the card or permanent that generated them. Continuous effects generated by the resolution of a spell or ability receive a timestamp when the spell or ability creating them res
olves.
\par 
\par Token
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
A token is an object in play representing a noncard permanent created by a spell or ability. Tokens can be tapped and untapped just like cards, though an alternative to rotation might be needed to distinguish their status. See rule 216, \'93Tokens.\'94

\par 
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 Tombstone Icon
\par A tombstone icon appears to the left of the name of many }{\i\f28\fs22 Odyssey }{\f28\fs22 block cards with abilities that are relevant in a player\rquote s graveyard. The purpose of the icon is to make those cards stand out when they\rquote 
re in a graveyard. This icon has no effect on game play.
\par 
\par Total Casting Cost (Obsolete)
\par Some older cards were printed with the term \'93total casting cost\'94 to describe the converted mana cost of a spell. In general, cards that were printed with the term \'93total casting cost\'94 now use the term \'93converted mana cost.\'94
\par 
\par Toughness
\par The number after the slash printed on the lower right corner of a creature card is the creature\rquote s toughness. A creature\rquote s current toughness is the initial value (the printed number), modified by any counters that adjust tou
ghness and then by any continuous effects.
\par      A creature that\rquote s been dealt damage greater than or equal to its toughness (and greater than 0) has lethal damage and will be destroyed the next time any player would receive priority. This is a state-based effect.
\par      A few creature cards have toughness represented by * instead of a number. This signifies that the creature has a static ability that sets its toughness according to some stated condition. If a spell or ability attempts to read the toughness whe
n the creature card isn\rquote t in play, the * is equal to 0.
\par 
\par Trample
\par }\pard\plain \s34\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f29\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\crauth1\crdate1716925069\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28 
Trample is a static ability modifying the combat damage step of the combat phase. It lets an attacking creature \'93trample over\'94 blocking creatures and assign part of its combat damage to the defending player. See rule 502.9, \'93Trample.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f12\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f28\fs22 
\par Trigger, Triggered Ability
\par A triggered ability begins with the word \'93when,\'94 \'93whenever,\'94 or \'93at.\'94 Whenever the trigger event occurs, the ability goes on top of the stack the next time a player would receive priority. See rule 404, \'93Triggered Abilities.\'94

\par 
\par Type
\par The word \'93type\'94 by itself is ambiguous\emdash it may mean the basic type of a card, spell, and so on, or the subtype of a creature, enchantment, or land. See rules 212\endash 215.
\par      A card\rquote s type (and subtype, if applicable) is printed directly below the illustration on the card. The spell type for a nonland card is the same as its card type, even if its rules text states it can be played \'93as\'94
 some other type (that is, following the timing rules for playing that other type). The permanent type for a card in play is the same as its card type. Tokens have no card or spell type but do have a permanent type.
\par      When a spell or ability changes a permanent\rquote s type, the new type replaces all previous types. If the spell or ability is adding a type, it will say so.
\par      A creature\rquote s type is printed after the word \'93creature\'94 below the illustration on the card or is defined by the spell or ability that created a token. A creature may have multiple types. A noncreature card that\rquote s c
hanged into a creature by a spell or ability has no creature type unless the spell or ability gives it one.
\par      A land\rquote s type is the same as its name.
\par      A local enchantment\rquote s type is printed after the word \'93Enchant\'94 on the card\rquote s type line.
\par      Categories of cards, such as basic land or local enchantment, aren\rquote t types or subtypes and can\rquote t be named when a type must be chosen.
\par      The \'93type\'94 of mana includes both its color (if any) and any restrictions placed upon it (for example, mana that can be used only to play artifact spells).
\par 
\par Unblockable
\par If an attacking creature \'93is unblockable,\'94 no creature can legally block it. Spells or abilities may still cause it to become blocked.
\par 
\par Unblocked Creature
\par An attacking creature becomes an unblocked creature during the declare blockers step of the combat phase if no creature blocks it. It remains an unblocked creature until a spell or ability causes it to become blocked, it\rquote 
s removed from combat, it stops being a creature, its controller changes, or the combat phase ends. Unblocked creatures don\rquote t exist outside of the combat phase or before the declare blockers step. See rule 309, \'93Declare Blockers Step.\'94
\par 
\par Unless
\par Some cards use the phrase \'93[Do something] unless you [do something else].\'94 This means the same thing as \'93You may [do something else]. If you don\rquote t, [do something].\'94
\par 
\par Untap
\par 1. To untap a tapped card, rotate it back to the upright position. }{\i\f28\fs22 See also}{\f28\fs22  Tap.
\par 2. Untap is the first step of the beginning phase of the turn. All permanents controlled by the active player normally untap at this time. See rule 302, \'93Untap Step.\'94
\par 
\par Upkeep
\par Upkeep is the second step of the beginning phase of the turn. Some cards have abilities that trigger at the beginning of the upkeep step; such an ability is called an \'93upkeep cos}{\f28\fs22\expnd4\expndtw20 t}{\f28\fs22 \'94 or an \'93upkeep effect.
\'94 An upkeep cost is usually written in the form \'93At the beginning of your upkeep, you may [pay cost]. If you don\rquote t, sacrifice [this card].\'94 See rule 303, \'93Upkeep Step.\'94
\par 
\par }{\i\f28\fs22 Vanguard}{\f28\fs22  Card
\par The }{\i\f28\fs22 Vanguard\'99}{\f28\fs22  supplements consist of oversized cards that modify the game. A }{\i\f28\fs22 Vanguard}{\f28\fs22  card is selected before the game begins, adjusting a player\rquote 
s starting and maximum hand size and starting life total. Any abilities printed on a }{\i\f28\fs22 Vanguard}{\f28\fs22  card are played exactly like those of an in-play }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22 
 card; however, these abilities have no color, and damage from them isn\rquote t damage from a permanent of any type or a source of any color. A }{\i\f28\fs22 Vanguard}{\f28\fs22  card isn\rquote t a }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic}{\f28\fs22  card, so it can\rquote 
t be affected by spells or abilities.
\par 
\par Wall
\par A Wall is a type of creature that can\rquote t be declared as an attacker. In all other respects, a Wall is the same as any other creature.
\par 
\par X
\par If a cost has an \'93X\'94 in it, the value of X must be announced as part of playing the spell or ability. (See rule 409, \'93Playing Spells and Abilities.\'94
) While the spell or ability is on the stack, the X in its mana cost equals that amount of generic mana. If a card in any other zone has X in its mana cost, the amount is treated as 0. If you\rquote re playing a spell without paying its 
mana cost and that spell has X in its mana cost, X is 0.
\par      In triggered abilities, X is defined when the ability resolves. It may be defined by the text of the ability, by a keyword ability of the card, or by the trigger event.
\par      In other cases, X is defined by the text of a spell or ability. If X isn\rquote t defined, the controller of the spell or ability chooses the value of X. All Xs on a card have the same value.
\par 
\par Y, Z
\par }{\i\f28\fs22 See}{\f28\fs22  X.
\par 
\par Yield Priority (Obsolete)
\par In earlier versions of the rules, the term \'93yield priority\'94 was used instead of \'93pass.\'94
\par 
\par You, Your
\par The words \'93you\'94 and \'93your\'94 on a card or permanent refer to the spell or ability\rquote s controller. For static abilities, this is the current controller of the card or permanent (or the card\rquote s owner if it isn\rquote t in 
play). For activated abilities, this is the player who played the ability. For triggered abilities, this is the controller of the card when the ability triggered (or the card\rquote s owner if it wasn\rquote t in play).
\par 
\par Zone
\par A zone is any place that }{\b\f28\fs22 Magic }{\f28\fs22 cards can be during a game. See rule 217, \'93Zones.\'94}{\f28 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx440\tx740\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f28\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
